{"title_page": "Jack Brooksbank", "text_new": "{{short description|Wine merchant, brand ambassor and husband to Princess Eugenie}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| name               = Jack Christopher Stamp Brooksbank\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1986|05|03|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[St Thomas\u2019s Hospital]], [[London]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British\n| education          = [[Stowe School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Bristol]]\n| occupation         = Businessman\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Princess Eugenie of York]]|12 October 2018}}\n}}\n\n'''Jack Christopher Stamp Brooksbank''' (born 3 May 1986) is a British wine merchant and brand ambassador who is the husband of [[Princess Eugenie]], a granddaughter of [[Queen Elizabeth II]].<ref name=tele />\n\n==Early life and family==\n[[File:Blas\u00f3n_de_los_Baronets_Brooksbank.svg|thumb|170px|Coat of arms of the [[Brooksbank baronets]]]]\nBrooksbank was born on 3 May 1986 at [[St Thomas' Hospital]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/TheDukeOfYork/status/1050434703189270528|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> In [[London]], the eldest son of George Edward Hugh Brooksbank and his wife, Nicola (n\u00e9e Newton). Brooksbank is [[Hereditary peer#Inheritance of titles|in remainder]] to the [[Brooksbank baronets|Brooksbank baronetcy]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Dangremond |url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/a21936749/jack-brooksbank-parents-family-facts/ |title=6 Things to Know About Jack Brooksbank's Family Ahead of His Wedding to Princess Eugenie |work=Town and Country |date=10 October 2018 |accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref> \n\nA half-third cousin twice-removed of Princess Eugenie through [[Thomas Coke, 2nd Earl of Leicester]],<ref name=Silverman>{{cite news |last=Silverman |first=Rose |title=Who is Jack Brooksbank, the wine merchant fianc\u00e9 of Princess Eugenie? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/relationships/has-one-infectious-laughs-jack-brooksbank-wine-merchant-fiance/ |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |access-date=24 January 2018 |date=22 January 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=notes|[[Thomas Coke, 2nd Earl of Leicester]], is Princess Eugenie's maternal great-great-great-great-grandfather (via [[Sarah, Duchess of York]]); Lord Leicester was also Brooksbank's great-great-grandfather via his second marriage, to [[the Hon.]] Georgina Cavendish.}} Brooksbank's great-grandfather was [[Thomas Coke, 2nd Earl of Leicester#Sir Jack Coke|Sir Jack Coke]], a [[Gentleman Usher]] to [[King George VI]] and Extra Gentleman Usher to [[Queen Elizabeth II]] and his great-uncle was [[John d'Henin Hamilton, 3rd Baron Hamilton of Dalzell|the 3rd Baron Hamilton of Dalzell]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=q5ghAAAAYAAJ&q=3rd+lord+hamilton+of+dalzell++celia++brooksbank&dq=3rd+lord+hamilton+of+dalzell++celia++brooksbank|title=Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage 1990|last1=Kidd|first1=C.|publisher=Debrett's Peerage|date= 1990|accessdate=25 October 2018|quote=....Rosemary Olive (Baroness Hamilton of Dalzell), b 1910: m 1935, 3rd Baron Hamilton of Dalzell. Residence \u2013 Garden Cottage, Snowdenham House, Bramley, Guildford.\u2014 Celia Dorothy, b 1919: m 1942, Stamp Godfrey Brooksbank, Capt ...|isbn=9780333388471}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Burgess |first1=K. |title=Princess Eugenie to marry in autumn |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/princess-eugenie-to-marry-in-autumn-nzb69f72j |newspaper=The Times| date = 22 January 2018 |accessdate=11 October 2018 |quote=He is a descendant of the Brooksbank baronets and his ancestors include Stamp Brooksbank, a governor of the Bank of England in the 18th century, Thomas Coke, second Earl of Leicester, and Sir John (Jack) Spencer Coke, who was gentleman usher to King George VI.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Black |first1=A and C |title=Who was who: A Companion to Who's Who |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Wg7YAAAAMAAJ&q=gentleman+usher+george+VI+Sir+John+Coke&dq=gentleman+usher+george+VI+Sir+John+Coke |publisher=A. & C. Black, 1961 |accessdate=11 October 2018 |quote=COKE, Major Hon. Sir John (Spencer), K.C.V.O., or. 1953 (C.V.O. 1946); Scots Guards, retired ; Extra Gentleman Usher to the Queen since 1952 (Gentleman Usher in Ordinary, ...|year=1961 }}</ref> His parents are [[Eton College|Old Etonian]] George Brooksbank,<ref name=\"Debrett's\">{{cite book |last1=Kidd |first1=Charles |title=Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage |url=https://books.google.com/?id=9w4MAQAAMAAJ&q=jack++brooksbank++great++grandson++baronet++eton++george&dq=jack++brooksbank++great++grandson++baronet++eton++george |publisher=Debrett's Peerage \u2013 1 June 1990 |accessdate=21 September 2018 |quote=B 130 \u2013 Brooksbank (1919).... George Edward Hugh, b 1949; ed Eton: m 1985, ... Jack born 1986, Thomas born 1988...|isbn=9780312046408 |date=June 1990 }}</ref> a company director and chartered accountant, and his wife, Nicola, who reside in London and [[Bordeaux]] in France. Jack has a younger brother, Thomas, who is also an Old Etonian.<ref name=\"Debrett's\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tominey |first1=C. |title=Princess Eugenie's future mother-in-law 'excited' as son weds into monarchy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2018/10/06/princess-eugenies-future-mother-in-law-excited-son-weds-monarchy/ |publisher=UK Daily Telegraph \u2013 6 October 2018 |accessdate=8 October 2018 |quote=Tom is an Old Etonian, like their father, George, and is believed to be the best man on the big day....The couple split their time between London and France's Bordeaux wine region where they own a three-bedroom stone farmhouse |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=6 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Education and career==\nBrooksbank was educated at [[Stowe School]] in [[Buckinghamshire]], before studying at the [[University of Bristol]] before leaving to work in the bar industry.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Puente |first1=M. |title=Princess Eugenie's groom: Who is Jack Brooksbank? And how does he know George Clooney? |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2018/10/11/princess-eugenies-commoner-groom-who-jack-brooksbank/1594124002/ |publisher=USA TODAY \u2013 11 October 2018 |accessdate=18 October 2018 |quote=But unlike Eugenie, who graduated from Newcastle University in 2009 with a degree in art and English literature, Brooksbank left Bristol University and went into the restaurant and bar industry, working first as a bartender.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45800373|title=Meet the bride and groom|date=11 October 2018|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2018|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC News}}</ref> He was the general manager of [[Mahiki]], a nightclub in Mayfair that was often visited by his wife's cousins [[Prince William]] and [[Prince Harry]] in their youth. He now works as a brand ambassador for [[Casamigos]] [[tequila]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/02018012241970/eugenie-fiance-jack-brooksbank-george-clooney|title=Princess Eugenie's fianc\u00e9 Jack Brooksbank has a connection to George Clooney|first=HELLO!|last=Canada|website=ca.hellomagazine.com|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\n{{Main article|Wedding of Princess Eugenie and Jack Brooksbank}}\nIn 2011, Brooksbank began dating [[Princess Eugenie of York]], the younger daughter of [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]], and [[Sarah, Duchess of York]]. On 22 January 2018, the Duke of York's office at [[Buckingham Palace]] announced their engagement.<ref name=\"Boyle and Furness\">{{cite news |last=Boyle |first=Danny|last2=Furness |first2=Hannah |title=Princess Eugenie engaged to Jack Brooksbank: Couple 'float with laughter and love', says Duchess of York in gushing tweets |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/22/princess-eugenie-marry-jack-brooksbankbuckingham-palace-announces/ |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=24 January 2018 |date=22 January 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn April 2018, the couple moved from their residence at [[St James's Palace]] to [[Ivy Cottage]], in the grounds of [[Kensington Palace]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://people.com/royals/princess-eugenie-jack-brooksbank-move-kensington-palace/|title=Princess Eugenie and Her Fianc\u00e9 Jack Brooksbank Just Moved Next Door to Harry and Meghan!|magazine=People|first=Simon|last=Perry|date=1 May 2018|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nTheir wedding took place on 12 October 2018 at [[St George's Chapel, Windsor Castle|St George's Chapel, Windsor]].<ref name=tele>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2018/10/12/princess-eugenies-royal-wedding-jack-brooksbank-live-updates/|title=Princess Eugenie's royal wedding to Jack Brooksbank: Live updates from the Windsor Castle celebrations|last=Davies|first=Gareth|date=12 October 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=12 October 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Contrary to press speculation that Brooksbank would be created \"Earl of Northallerton\", he has not been elevated to the [[Peerage of the United Kingdom|peerage]] after marrying into the royal family, following a trend in recent years for a male commoner not to be awarded one upon marriage to a princess.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/a22515482/jack-brooksbank-royal-title/ |title=Jack Brooksbank Royal Title \u2013 Why Princess Eugenie's Fianc\u00e9 Won't Get a Title |publisher=Townandcountrymag.com |date=11 October 2018 |accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2018/10/12/how-come-princess-eugenie-commoner-groom-didnt-get-title/1594927002/ |title=Why didn't Princess Eugenie's commoner groom get a title? |newspaper=USA Today |date=12 October 2018 |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}} \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brooksbank, Jack Christopher Stamp}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People educated at Stowe School]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:House of Windsor|Jack]]\n[[Category:Brooksbank family|Jack]]\n[[Category:Mountbatten-Windsor family|Jack]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wine merchant, brand ambassor and husband to Princess Eugenie}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| name               = Jack Christopher Stamp Brooksbank\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1986|05|03|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[St Thomas\u2019s Hospital]], [[London]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British\n| education          = [[Stowe School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Bristol]]\n| occupation         = Businessman\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Princess Eugenie of York]]|12 October 2018}}\n}}\n\n'''Jack Christopher Stamp Brooksbank''' (born 3 May 1986) is a British wine merchant and brand ambassador who is the husband of [[Princess Eugenie]], a granddaughter of [[Queen Elizabeth II]].<ref name=tele />\n\n==Early life and family==\n[[File:Blas\u00f3n_de_los_Baronets_Brooksbank.svg|thumb|170px|Coat of arms of the [[Brooksbank baronets]]]]\nBrooksbank was born on 3 May 1986 at [[St Thomas' Hospital]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/TheDukeOfYork/status/1050434703189270528|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> In [[London]], the eldest son of George Edward Hugh Brooksbank and his wife, Nicola (n\u00e9e Newton). Brooksbank is [[Hereditary peer#Inheritance of titles|in remainder]] to the [[Brooksbank baronets|Brooksbank baronetcy]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Dangremond |url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/a21936749/jack-brooksbank-parents-family-facts/ |title=6 Things to Know About Jack Brooksbank's Family Ahead of His Wedding to Princess Eugenie |work=Town and Country |date=10 October 2018 |accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref> \n\nA half-third cousin twice-removed of Princess Eugenie through [[Thomas Coke, 2nd Earl of Leicester]],<ref name=Silverman>{{cite news |last=Silverman |first=Rose |title=Who is Jack Brooksbank, the wine merchant fianc\u00e9 of Princess Eugenie? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/relationships/has-one-infectious-laughs-jack-brooksbank-wine-merchant-fiance/ |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |access-date=24 January 2018 |date=22 January 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=notes|[[Thomas Coke, 2nd Earl of Leicester]], is Princess Eugenie's maternal great-great-great-great-grandfather (via [[Sarah, Duchess of York]]); Lord Leicester was also Brooksbank's great-great-grandfather via his second marriage, to [[the Hon.]] Georgina Cavendish.}} Brooksbank's great-grandfather was [[Thomas Coke, 2nd Earl of Leicester#Sir Jack Coke|Sir Jack Coke]], a [[Gentleman Usher]] to [[King George VI]] and Extra Gentleman Usher to [[Queen Elizabeth II]] and his great-uncle was [[John d'Henin Hamilton, 3rd Baron Hamilton of Dalzell|the 3rd Baron Hamilton of Dalzell]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=q5ghAAAAYAAJ&q=3rd+lord+hamilton+of+dalzell++celia++brooksbank&dq=3rd+lord+hamilton+of+dalzell++celia++brooksbank|title=Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage 1990|last1=Kidd|first1=C.|publisher=Debrett's Peerage|date= 1990|accessdate=25 October 2018|quote=....Rosemary Olive (Baroness Hamilton of Dalzell), b 1910: m 1935, 3rd Baron Hamilton of Dalzell. Residence \u2013 Garden Cottage, Snowdenham House, Bramley, Guildford.\u2014 Celia Dorothy, b 1919: m 1942, Stamp Godfrey Brooksbank, Capt ...|isbn=9780333388471}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Burgess |first1=K. |title=Princess Eugenie to marry in autumn |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/princess-eugenie-to-marry-in-autumn-nzb69f72j |newspaper=The Times| date = 22 January 2018 |accessdate=11 October 2018 |quote=He is a descendant of the Brooksbank baronets and his ancestors include Stamp Brooksbank, a governor of the Bank of England in the 18th century, Thomas Coke, second Earl of Leicester, and Sir John (Jack) Spencer Coke, who was gentleman usher to King George VI.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Black |first1=A and C |title=Who was who: A Companion to Who's Who |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Wg7YAAAAMAAJ&q=gentleman+usher+george+VI+Sir+John+Coke&dq=gentleman+usher+george+VI+Sir+John+Coke |publisher=A. & C. Black, 1961 |accessdate=11 October 2018 |quote=COKE, Major Hon. Sir John (Spencer), K.C.V.O., or. 1953 (C.V.O. 1946); Scots Guards, retired ; Extra Gentleman Usher to the Queen since 1952 (Gentleman Usher in Ordinary, ...|year=1961 }}</ref> His parents are [[Eton College|Old Etonian]] George Brooksbank,<ref name=\"Debrett's\">{{cite book |last1=Kidd |first1=Charles |title=Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage |url=https://books.google.com/?id=9w4MAQAAMAAJ&q=jack++brooksbank++great++grandson++baronet++eton++george&dq=jack++brooksbank++great++grandson++baronet++eton++george |publisher=Debrett's Peerage \u2013 1 June 1990 |accessdate=21 September 2018 |quote=B 130 \u2013 Brooksbank (1919).... George Edward Hugh, b 1949; ed Eton: m 1985, ... Jack born 1986, Thomas born 1988...|isbn=9780312046408 |date=June 1990 }}</ref> a company director and chartered accountant, and his wife, Nicola, who reside in London and [[Bordeaux]] in France. Jack has a younger brother, Thomas, who is also an Old Etonian.<ref name=\"Debrett's\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tominey |first1=C. |title=Princess Eugenie's future mother-in-law 'excited' as son weds into monarchy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2018/10/06/princess-eugenies-future-mother-in-law-excited-son-weds-monarchy/ |publisher=UK Daily Telegraph \u2013 6 October 2018 |accessdate=8 October 2018 |quote=Tom is an Old Etonian, like their father, George, and is believed to be the best man on the big day....The couple split their time between London and France's Bordeaux wine region where they own a three-bedroom stone farmhouse |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=6 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Education and career==\nBrooksbank was educated at [[Stowe School]] in [[Buckinghamshire]], before studying at the [[University of Bristol]] before leaving to work in the bar industry.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Puente |first1=M. |title=Princess Eugenie's groom: Who is Jack Brooksbank? And how does he know George Clooney? |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2018/10/11/princess-eugenies-commoner-groom-who-jack-brooksbank/1594124002/ |publisher=USA TODAY \u2013 11 October 2018 |accessdate=18 October 2018 |quote=But unlike Eugenie, who graduated from Newcastle University in 2009 with a degree in art and English literature, Brooksbank left Bristol University and went into the restaurant and bar industry, working first as a bartender.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45800373|title=Meet the bride and groom|date=11 October 2018|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2018|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC News}}</ref> He was the general manager of [[Mahiki]], a nightclub in Mayfair that was often visited by his wife's cousins [[Prince William]] and [[Prince Harry]] in their youth. He now works as a brand ambassador for [[Casamigos]] [[tequila]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/02018012241970/eugenie-fiance-jack-brooksbank-george-clooney|title=Princess Eugenie's fianc\u00e9 Jack Brooksbank has a connection to George Clooney|first=HELLO!|last=Canada|website=ca.hellomagazine.com|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\n{{Main article|Wedding of Princess Eugenie and Jack Brooksbank}}\nIn 2011, Brooksbank began dating [[Princess Eugenie of York]], the younger daughter of [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]], and [[Sarah, Duchess of York]]. On 22 January 2018, the Duke of York's office at [[Buckingham Palace]] announced their engagement.<ref name=\"Boyle and Furness\">{{cite news |last=Boyle |first=Danny|last2=Furness |first2=Hannah |title=Princess Eugenie engaged to Jack Brooksbank: Couple 'float with laughter and love', says Duchess of York in gushing tweets |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/22/princess-eugenie-marry-jack-brooksbankbuckingham-palace-announces/ |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=24 January 2018 |date=22 January 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn April 2018, the couple moved from their residence at [[St James's Palace]] to [[Ivy Cottage]], in the grounds of [[Kensington Palace]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://people.com/royals/princess-eugenie-jack-brooksbank-move-kensington-palace/|title=Princess Eugenie and Her Fianc\u00e9 Jack Brooksbank Just Moved Next Door to Harry and Meghan!|magazine=People|first=Simon|last=Perry|date=1 May 2018|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nTheir wedding took place on 12 October 2018 at [[St George's Chapel, Windsor Castle|St George's Chapel, Windsor]].<ref name=tele>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2018/10/12/princess-eugenies-royal-wedding-jack-brooksbank-live-updates/|title=Princess Eugenie's royal wedding to Jack Brooksbank: Live updates from the Windsor Castle celebrations|last=Davies|first=Gareth|date=12 October 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=12 October 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Contrary to press speculation that Brooksbank would be created \"Earl of Northallerton\", he has not been elevated to the [[Peerage of the United Kingdom|peerage]] after marrying into the royal family, following a trend in recent years for a male commoner not to be awarded one upon marriage to a princess.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/a22515482/jack-brooksbank-royal-title/ |title=Jack Brooksbank Royal Title \u2013 Why Princess Eugenie's Fianc\u00e9 Won't Get a Title |publisher=Townandcountrymag.com |date=11 October 2018 |accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2018/10/12/how-come-princess-eugenie-commoner-groom-didnt-get-title/1594927002/ |title=Why didn't Princess Eugenie's commoner groom get a title? |newspaper=USA Today |date=12 October 2018 |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}} \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brooksbank, Jack Christopher Stamp}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People educated at Stowe School]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:House of Windsor|Jack]\n[[Category:Brooksbank family|Jack]]\n[[Category:Mountbatten-Windsor family|Jack]]\n", "name_user": "Rcb1", "label": "safe", "comment": "bracket", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Brooksbank"}
{"title_page": "Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek", "text_new": "<!-- Article title: Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek SHRNo:1457 DatabaseNo:5051355 -->\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox bridge \n| name = Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| pushpin_map = New South Wales\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_map_size = 240\n| pushpin_map_alt = \n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in [[New South Wales]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|-32.5193|151.3523|region:AU-NSW_type:landmark|display=inline,title|format=dms}}\n| os_grid_reference = \n| qid = \n| refs = \n| carries = Main Road\n| crosses = Webbers Creek\n| locale = [[Glendon Brook, New South Wales|Glendon Brook]], [[Singleton Council]], [[New South Wales]], Australia \n| starts = | ends = | official_name = | other_name = | named_for = \n| owner = [[Roads and Maritime Services]] \n| maint = | heritage = | id = | id_type = | website = | preceded = | followed = \n| design = [[Truss bridge]]\n| material = Timber\n| material1 = \n| material2 = \n| length = {{convert|45.4|m|ft|0}}<br/>{{small|(including approaches)}}\n| width = {{convert|4.6|m|ft|0}}\n| height = \n| depth = \n| traversable = \n| towpath = \n| mainspan =  {{convert|27.7|m|ft|0}} \n| number_spans = One\n| piers_in_water = | load = | clearance_above = | clearance_below = | lanes = | life = | first_length = | first_diameter = | second_length = | second_diameter = | third_length = | third_diameter = | capacity = | num_track = | track_gauge = | structure_gauge = | electrification = | architect = \n| designer = [[Ernest de Burgh]] \n| contracted_designer = | winner = | engineering = | builder = | fabricator = | begin = | complete = \n| cost = [[Australian pound|A\u00a3]]1,875\n| open = 1902<!-- or | opening = --> \n| inaugurated = | rebuilt = | collapsed = | closed = | replaces = | replaced_by = | traffic = | toll = \n| map_type = \n| map_relief = \n| map_dot_label = \n| map_image = \n| map_size = \n| map_alt = \n| mapframe = yes\n| mapframe_zoom = 14\n| mapframe_width = \n| mapframe_height = \n| mapframe_marker = \n| mapframe_marker_color = \n| mapframe_lat = \n| mapframe_long = \n| map_caption = \n| extra = {{Infobox designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = New South Wales State Heritage Register\n| designation1_offname = Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek\n| designation1_type = State heritage (built)\n| designation1_date = 20 June 2000\n| delisted1_date = \n| designation1_partof = \n| designation1_number = 1457\n| designation1_free1name =  Type\n| designation1_free1value = Road Bridge\n| designation1_free2name =  Category\n| designation1_free2value = Transport - Land\n| designation1_free3name = Builders\n| designation1_free3value = W. T. Oakes, Sydney\n}} \n}}\nThe '''Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek''' is a heritage-listed timber [[Truss bridge|truss]] [[road bridge]] that carries Main Road across Webbers Creek, located in [[Glendon Brook, New South Wales|Glendon Brook]], [[Singleton Council]], [[New South Wales]], Australia. It was designed by [[Ernest de Burgh]]. The property is owned by [[Roads and Maritime Services]], an [[government agency|agency]] of the [[Government of New South Wales]]. It was added to the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 20 June 2000.<ref name=nswshr-1457>{{cite NSW SHR|5051355|Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek|hr=01457|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n===Timber truss bridges===\n\nTimber truss road bridges have played a significant role in the expansion and improvement of the NSW road network. Prior to the bridges being built, river crossings were often dangerous in times of rain, which caused bulk freight movement to be prohibitively expensive for most agricultural and mining produce. Only the high priced wool clip of the time was able to carry the costs and inconvenience imposed by the generally inadequate river crossings that often existed prior to the trusses construction.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nTimber truss bridges were preferred by the [[NSW Public Works|Public Works Department]] from the mid 19th to the early 20th century because they were relatively cheap to construct, and used mostly local materials. The financially troubled governments of the day applied pressure to the Public Works Department to produce as much road and bridge work for as little cost as possible, using local materials. This condition effectively prohibited the use of iron and steel, as these, prior to the construction of the steel works at [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]] in the early 20th century, had to be imported from England.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nErnest de Burgh, the designer of DeBurgh truss and other bridges, was a leading engineer with the Public Works Department, and a prominent figure in early 20th century NSW.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nTimber truss bridges, and timber bridges generally were so common that NSW was known to travellers as the \"timber bridge state\".<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n===Beckers Bridge===\n\nThe bridge was advertised for tender in 1901, with W. T. Oakes the successful contractor with a tender of [[Australian pound|A\u00a3]]1,875, and completed in 1902.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article122853754 |title=BRIDGE OVER DUNN'S CROSSING. |newspaper=[[The Maitland Daily Mercury]] |volume=7128 |issue=2375 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=19 August 1901 |accessdate=28 October 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref> It replaced the need to cross the river at water-level, which had been dangerous at higher levels.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article78914256 |title=BRANXTON. |newspaper=[[Singleton Argus]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 September 1901 |accessdate=28 October 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article126599994 |title=District Intelligence. |newspaper=[[The Maitland Weekly Mercury]] |volume=7128 |issue=451 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 August 1902 |accessdate=28 October 2018 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nA 2011 report profiling timber truss road bridges found that Beckers Bridge could not be upgraded to a required standard and would need to be replaced. Following this, the 2012 Roads and Maritime Services Timber Truss Bridge Conservation Strategy identified Beckers Bridge as a target to be removed and replaced in the future. It stated that, although all submissions received had been in support of its retention, it could not meet the load requirements necessary for the route and described it as \"an unremarkable example of its type\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/projects/key-build-programs/maintenance/timber-truss-road-bridges/timber-tuss-abercrombie-bridge-wee-jasper-bridge.pdf | title=Individual Bridge Profiles - Timber Truss Road Bridges | publisher=Roads and Management Services | accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/projects/key-build-programs/maintenance/timber-truss-road-bridges/120800-timber-truss-bridges-subs-revised-strategy-august-2012.pdf | title=Timber Truss Bridge Conservation Strategyq | publisher=Roads and Maritime Services | accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Michael Johnsen]], the local MP in the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]], published a call for feedback on the design and alignment of a new bridge, after the completion of which the original bridge would be demolished.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.michaeljohnsen.com.au/releases/say-beckers-bridge-replacement/ | title=Have Your Say On Beckers Bridge Replacement | publisher=Michael Johnsen MP | accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref> In 2018, its State Heritage Register listing refers to it as \"under consideration for removal\".<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n== Description ==\nBecker's Bridge is a DeBurgh type timber [[truss]] road bridge. It has a single timber truss [[Span (architecture)|span]] of {{convert|27.7|m|ft|0}}. There is a single timber approach span at each end giving the bridge an overall length of {{convert|45.4|m|ft|0}}.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nThe superstructure is supported by timber trestles and provides a carriage way with a minimum width of {{convert|4.6|m|ft|0}}. The guard rail is of timber post and rail construction and extends the full length of the bridge.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n== Heritage listing ==\nCompleted in 1902, Beckers Bridge is an early example of a DeBurgh timber truss road bridge. In 1998 it was in good condition. As a timber truss road bridge, it has many associational links with important historical events, trends, and people, including the expansion of the road network and economic activity throughout NSW, and Ernest DeBurgh, the designer of this type of truss. DeBurgh trusses were fourth in the five stage design evolution of NSW timber truss road bridges. Designed by Public Works engineer Ernest M. DeBurgh, the DeBurgh truss is an adaptation of the American Pratt truss design. The DeBurgh truss is the first to use significant amounts of steel and iron, and did so in spite of its high cost and the government's historical preference for timber.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nDeBurgh trusses were significant technical improvements over their predecessors. Situated in the Hunter region, Beckers bridge gains heritage significance because of its proximity to 15 other historic bridges, each constructed before 1905. In 1998 there were 10 surviving DeBurgh trusses in NSW of the 20 built, and 82 timber truss road bridges survive from the over 400 built. The Beckers bridge is a representative example of DeBurgh timber truss road bridges, and is assessed as being State significant, primarily on the basis of its technical and historical significance.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nBeckers Bridge over Webbers Creek was listed on the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 20 June 2000 having satisfied the following criteria.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the course, or pattern, of cultural or natural history in New South Wales.'''\n\nThrough the bridge's association with the expansion of the NSW road network, its ability to demonstrate historically important concepts such as the gradual acceptance of NSW people of American design ideas, and its association with Ernest DeBurgh, it has historical significance.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating aesthetic characteristics and/or a high degree of creative or technical achievement in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe bridge exhibits the technical excellence of its design, as all of the structural detail is clearly visible. In the context of its landscape it is visually attractive. As such, the bridge has a small amount of aesthetic significance.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n'''The place has a strong or special association with a particular community or cultural group in New South Wales for social, cultural or spiritual reasons.'''\n\nTimber truss bridges are prominent to road travellers, and NSW has in the past been referred to as the \"timber truss bridge state\". Through this, the complete set of bridges gain some social significance, as they could be said to be held in reasonable esteem by many travellers in NSW.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n'''The place possesses uncommon, rare or endangered aspects of the cultural or natural history of New South Wales.'''\n\nThe bridge is rare - an early example of DeBurgh trusses.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the principal characteristics of a class of cultural or natural places/environments in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe bridge is representative of DeBurgh truss bridges.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{Portal|New South Wales|Transport|Engineering|Australian roads}}}}\n* [[List of bridges in Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite web|author=Attraction Homepagework=Roads and Traffic Authority|date=2007|title=Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek|url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/index.cgi?action=heritage.show&id=4300128}}\n* {{cite book|work=Department of Main Roads, NSW|date=1987|title=Timber Truss Bridge Maintenance Handbook}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Fletcher, Robert |author2=Snow, J. P.|date=1934|title=A History of Development of Wood Bridges}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fraser|first=D. J.|date=1985|title=Timber Bridges in NSW}}\n* {{cite book|author=Martindale, Capt. B. H.|date=1857|title=Reports on Inland Communication}}\n* {{cite web|work=Roads and Traffic Authority|date=|title=S. 170 Register|url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/index.cgi?action=heritage.show&id=4300128}}\n=== Attribution ===\n{{NSW-SHR-CC|name=Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek|dno=5051355|id=1457|year=2018|accessdate=13 October 2018}}\n\n{{Road infrastructure in regional New South Wales}}\n\n[[Category:New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:Glendon Brook, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Articles incorporating text from the New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:1902 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1902]]\n[[Category:Wooden bridges in Australia]]\n[[Category:Truss bridges in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Article title: Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek SHRNo:1457 DatabaseNo:5051355 -->\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox bridge \n| name = Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| pushpin_map = New South Wales\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_map_size = 240\n| pushpin_map_alt = \n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in [[New South Wales]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|-32.5193|151.3523|region:AU-NSW_type:landmark|display=inline,title|format=dms}}\n| os_grid_reference = \n| qid = \n| refs = \n| carries = Main Road\n| crosses = Webbers Creek\n| locale = [[Glendon Brook, New South Wales|Glendon Brook]], [[Singleton Council]], [[New South Wales]], Australia \n| starts = | ends = | official_name = | other_name = | named_for = \n| owner = [[Roads and Maritime Services]] \n| maint = | heritage = | id = | id_type = | website = | preceded = | followed = \n| design = [[Truss bridge]]\n| material = Timber\n| material1 = \n| material2 = \n| length = {{convert|45.4|m|ft|0}}<br/>{{small|(including approaches)}}\n| width = {{convert|4.6|m|ft|0}}\n| height = \n| depth = \n| traversable = \n| towpath = \n| mainspan =  {{convert|27.7|m|ft|0}} \n| number_spans = One\n| piers_in_water = | load = | clearance_above = | clearance_below = | lanes = | life = | first_length = | first_diameter = | second_length = | second_diameter = | third_length = | third_diameter = | capacity = | num_track = | track_gauge = | structure_gauge = | electrification = | architect = \n| designer = [[Ernest de Burgh]] \n| contracted_designer = | winner = | engineering = | builder = | fabricator = | begin = | complete = \n| cost = [[Australian pound|A\u00a3]]1,875\n| open = 1902<!-- or | opening = --> \n| inaugurated = | rebuilt = | collapsed = | closed = | replaces = | replaced_by = | traffic = | toll = | map_type = | map_relief = | map_dot_label = | map_image = | map_size = | map_alt = | mapframe = | mapframe_zoom = | mapframe_width = | mapframe_height = | mapframe_marker = | mapframe_marker_color = | mapframe_lat = | mapframe_long = | map_caption = \n| extra = {{Infobox designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = New South Wales State Heritage Register\n| designation1_offname = Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek\n| designation1_type = State heritage (built)\n| designation1_date = 20 June 2000\n| delisted1_date = \n| designation1_partof = \n| designation1_number = 1457\n| designation1_free1name =  Type\n| designation1_free1value = Road Bridge\n| designation1_free2name =  Category\n| designation1_free2value = Transport - Land\n| designation1_free3name = Builders\n| designation1_free3value = W. T. Oakes, Sydney\n}} \n}}\nThe '''Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek''' is a heritage-listed timber [[Truss bridge|truss]] [[road bridge]] that carries Main Road across Webbers Creek, located in [[Glendon Brook, New South Wales|Glendon Brook]], [[Singleton Council]], [[New South Wales]], Australia. It was designed by [[Ernest de Burgh]]. The property is owned by [[Roads and Maritime Services]], an [[government agency|agency]] of the [[Government of New South Wales]]. It was added to the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 20 June 2000.<ref name=nswshr-1457>{{cite NSW SHR|5051355|Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek|hr=01457|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n===Timber truss bridges===\n\nTimber truss road bridges have played a significant role in the expansion and improvement of the NSW road network. Prior to the bridges being built, river crossings were often dangerous in times of rain, which caused bulk freight movement to be prohibitively expensive for most agricultural and mining produce. Only the high priced wool clip of the time was able to carry the costs and inconvenience imposed by the generally inadequate river crossings that often existed prior to the trusses construction.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nTimber truss bridges were preferred by the [[NSW Public Works|Public Works Department]] from the mid 19th to the early 20th century because they were relatively cheap to construct, and used mostly local materials. The financially troubled governments of the day applied pressure to the Public Works Department to produce as much road and bridge work for as little cost as possible, using local materials. This condition effectively prohibited the use of iron and steel, as these, prior to the construction of the steel works at [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]] in the early 20th century, had to be imported from England.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nErnest de Burgh, the designer of DeBurgh truss and other bridges, was a leading engineer with the Public Works Department, and a prominent figure in early 20th century NSW.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nTimber truss bridges, and timber bridges generally were so common that NSW was known to travellers as the \"timber bridge state\".<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n===Beckers Bridge===\n\nThe bridge was advertised for tender in 1901, with W. T. Oakes the successful contractor with a tender of [[Australian pound|A\u00a3]]1,875, and completed in 1902.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article122853754 |title=BRIDGE OVER DUNN'S CROSSING. |newspaper=[[The Maitland Daily Mercury]] |volume=7128 |issue=2375 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=19 August 1901 |accessdate=28 October 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref> It replaced the need to cross the river at water-level, which had been dangerous at higher levels.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article78914256 |title=BRANXTON. |newspaper=[[Singleton Argus]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 September 1901 |accessdate=28 October 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article126599994 |title=District Intelligence. |newspaper=[[The Maitland Weekly Mercury]] |volume=7128 |issue=451 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 August 1902 |accessdate=28 October 2018 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nA 2011 report profiling timber truss road bridges found that Beckers Bridge could not be upgraded to a required standard and would need to be replaced. Following this, the 2012 Roads and Maritime Services Timber Truss Bridge Conservation Strategy identified Beckers Bridge as a target to be removed and replaced in the future. It stated that, although all submissions received had been in support of its retention, it could not meet the load requirements necessary for the route and described it as \"an unremarkable example of its type\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/projects/key-build-programs/maintenance/timber-truss-road-bridges/timber-tuss-abercrombie-bridge-wee-jasper-bridge.pdf | title=Individual Bridge Profiles - Timber Truss Road Bridges | publisher=Roads and Management Services | accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/projects/key-build-programs/maintenance/timber-truss-road-bridges/120800-timber-truss-bridges-subs-revised-strategy-august-2012.pdf | title=Timber Truss Bridge Conservation Strategyq | publisher=Roads and Maritime Services | accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Michael Johnsen]], the local MP in the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]], published a call for feedback on the design and alignment of a new bridge, after the completion of which the original bridge would be demolished.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.michaeljohnsen.com.au/releases/say-beckers-bridge-replacement/ | title=Have Your Say On Beckers Bridge Replacement | publisher=Michael Johnsen MP | accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref> In 2018, its State Heritage Register listing refers to it as \"under consideration for removal\".<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n== Description ==\nBecker's Bridge is a DeBurgh type timber [[truss]] road bridge. It has a single timber truss [[Span (architecture)|span]] of {{convert|27.7|m|ft|0}}. There is a single timber approach span at each end giving the bridge an overall length of {{convert|45.4|m|ft|0}}.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nThe superstructure is supported by timber trestles and provides a carriage way with a minimum width of {{convert|4.6|m|ft|0}}. The guard rail is of timber post and rail construction and extends the full length of the bridge.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n== Heritage listing ==\nCompleted in 1902, Beckers Bridge is an early example of a DeBurgh timber truss road bridge. In 1998 it was in good condition. As a timber truss road bridge, it has many associational links with important historical events, trends, and people, including the expansion of the road network and economic activity throughout NSW, and Ernest DeBurgh, the designer of this type of truss. DeBurgh trusses were fourth in the five stage design evolution of NSW timber truss road bridges. Designed by Public Works engineer Ernest M. DeBurgh, the DeBurgh truss is an adaptation of the American Pratt truss design. The DeBurgh truss is the first to use significant amounts of steel and iron, and did so in spite of its high cost and the government's historical preference for timber.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nDeBurgh trusses were significant technical improvements over their predecessors. Situated in the Hunter region, Beckers bridge gains heritage significance because of its proximity to 15 other historic bridges, each constructed before 1905. In 1998 there were 10 surviving DeBurgh trusses in NSW of the 20 built, and 82 timber truss road bridges survive from the over 400 built. The Beckers bridge is a representative example of DeBurgh timber truss road bridges, and is assessed as being State significant, primarily on the basis of its technical and historical significance.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\nBeckers Bridge over Webbers Creek was listed on the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 20 June 2000 having satisfied the following criteria.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the course, or pattern, of cultural or natural history in New South Wales.'''\n\nThrough the bridge's association with the expansion of the NSW road network, its ability to demonstrate historically important concepts such as the gradual acceptance of NSW people of American design ideas, and its association with Ernest DeBurgh, it has historical significance.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating aesthetic characteristics and/or a high degree of creative or technical achievement in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe bridge exhibits the technical excellence of its design, as all of the structural detail is clearly visible. In the context of its landscape it is visually attractive. As such, the bridge has a small amount of aesthetic significance.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n'''The place has a strong or special association with a particular community or cultural group in New South Wales for social, cultural or spiritual reasons.'''\n\nTimber truss bridges are prominent to road travellers, and NSW has in the past been referred to as the \"timber truss bridge state\". Through this, the complete set of bridges gain some social significance, as they could be said to be held in reasonable esteem by many travellers in NSW.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n'''The place possesses uncommon, rare or endangered aspects of the cultural or natural history of New South Wales.'''\n\nThe bridge is rare - an early example of DeBurgh trusses.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the principal characteristics of a class of cultural or natural places/environments in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe bridge is representative of DeBurgh truss bridges.<ref name=nswshr-1457/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{portal|New South Wales|Australian roads}}}}\n* [[List of bridges in Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite web|author=Attraction Homepage|date=2007|title=Beckers Bridge over Webbers Creek|url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/index.cgi?action=heritage.show&id=4300128}}\n* {{cite book|author=Department of Main Roads, NSW|date=1987|title=Timber Truss Bridge Maintenance Handbook}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Fletcher, Robert |author2=Snow, J. P.|date=1934|title=A History of Development of Wood Bridges}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fraser|first=D. J.|date=1985|title=Timber Bridges in NSW}}\