 seconds/reserves team from 1925 until 1999, and will begin to do so again from the 2018 season. From 1919 to 1991 the VFL/AFL operated a [[reserve team|reserves competition]], and from 1992 to 1999 a ''de facto'' AFL reserves competition was run by the [[Victorian State Football League]], and North Melbourne fielded its reserves team in both of these competitions while it was in the VFL/AFL, allowing players who were not selected for the senior team to play for North Melbourne in the lower grade. During that time, the North Melbourne reserves team won seven premierships (1947, 1957, 1967, 1978, 1979, 1995, 1996).\n\nFollowing the demise of the AFL reserves competition, North Melbourne's reserves team was dissolved, and over the following eighteen years the club entered [[Australian Football League reserves affiliations|reserves affiliations]] with a range of [[Victorian Football League]] clubs. Under the affiliations, reserves players for North Melbourne play VFL football with one of the affiliated clubs. The club had five different affiliation arrangements over that time:\n*2000\u20132002 \u2013 [[Murray Kangaroos Football Club|Murray Kangaroos]]\n*2003\u20132005 \u2013 [[Port Melbourne Football Club|Port Melbourne]]\n*2006\u20132007 \u2013 [[North Ballarat Football Club|North Ballarat]] and [[Tasmanian Devils Football Club|Tasmania]]\n*2008\u20132015 \u2013 [[North Ballarat Football Club|North Ballarat]] and [[Werribee Football Club|Werribee]]\n*2016\u20132017 \u2013 [[Werribee Football Club|Werribee]]<ref name=\"NMNB\">{{cite news |newspaper=Herald Sun |location=Melbourne, VIC |author=Glenn McFarline |date=21 November 2014 |accessdate=22 November 2014 |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/North-melbourne-is-set-to-end-its-partnership-with-ballarat-as-western-bulldogs-move-in/story-fni5f986-1227131173808 |title=North Melbourne is set to end its partnership with Ballarat as Western Bulldogs move in}}</ref>\n\nStarting in the [[2018 VFL season]], North Melbourne re-established its own reserves team, which will play in the VFL. It played its home games at [[Chirnside Park (stadium)|Chirnside Park]] in Werribee until mid-2019,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/teams/North-melbourne/North-melbourne-to-field-standalone-vfl-team-in-2018-after-parting-ways-with-werribee/news-story/8cbc653bd3977b87931d68f21496b64f |title=North Melbourne to field standalone VFL team in 2018 after parting ways with Werribee |first=Ben |last=Higgins |newspaper=[[Herald Sun]] |date=24 April 2017}}</ref> and then began playing at Arden Street Oval.\n\n==Women's teams==\nIn 2017, following the inaugural [[AFL Women's]] (AFLW) season, North Melbourne was among eight clubs that applied for licences to enter the competition from 2019 onwards.<ref>{{cite news |last=Schmook |first=Nathan |title=Decision on AFLW expansion delayed |url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-08-29/decision-over-aflw-expansion-delayed |work=afl.com.au |date=29 August 2017 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> In September 2017, the club was announced as one of two clubs, along with {{AFLW Gee}}, to receive a licence to join the competition in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Black |first=Sarah |title=North and Geelong win AFLW expansion race |url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-09-27/afl-set-to-reveal-new-womens-teams-for-2019 |work=afl.com.au |date=27 September 2017 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> In April 2018, the club announced the signing of {{AFLW WB}} midfielder [[Emma Kearney (sportswoman)|Emma Kearney]], who had just won the [[AFL Women's best and fairest]] and a [[List of AFL Women's premiers|premiership]] and club best-and-fairest with the Bulldogs.<ref>{{cite news |title=AFLW: Recruiting coup as star Dog joins Roos |url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2018-04-04/aflw-star-bulldog-walks-out-to-join-roos |work=afl.com.au |date=4 April 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gabelich |first=Josh |title=North Melbourne reels in AFLW's biggest fish, landing Western Bulldogs star Emma Kearney |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/North-melbourne-reels-in-aflws-biggest-fish-landing-western-bulldogs-star-emma-kearney/news-story/06ae75493f9486e090aa40a6c6372c1f |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]] |date=5 April 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cherny |first=Daniel |title=Emma Kearney opens up on leaving the Bulldogs for North Melbourne |url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/emma-kearney-leaving-bulldogs-North-melbourne-20180405-p4z7y6.html |work=[[The Age]] |date=5 April 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> North Melbourne began fielding a team in the second-tier [[VFL Women's]] league in 2020.\n\n{{North Melbourne AFL Women's current squad}}\n\n=== Season summaries ===\n'''AFL Women's'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%\"\n! colspan=\"9\" | North Melbourne AFLW honour roll\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%;\"\n! Season !! Final position\n!Coach\n!Captain!! Best and fairest !! Leading goal kicker\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|[[2019 AFL Women's season|2019]]\n|3rd ^\n|[[Scott Gowans]]\n|[[Emma Kearney (sportswoman)|Emma Kearney]]\n|[[Jenna Bruton]]\n|[[Emma King (footballer)|Emma King]] (8)\n|-\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|[[2020 AFL Women's season|2020]]\n|2nd ^\n|[[Scott Gowans]]\n|[[Emma Kearney (sportswoman)|Emma Kearney]]\n|TBC\n|[[Kaitlyn Ashmore]] (9)\n|-\n|}\n<small>^ Denotes the ladder was split into two or more conferences. These numbers refer to the club's overall finishing position that season.</small>\n\n'''VFL Women's'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%\"\n! colspan=\"9\" | North Melbourne VFLW honour roll\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%;\"\n! Season !! Final position\n!Coach\n!Captain!! Best and fairest !! Leading goal kicker\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|[[2020 VFL season|2020]]\n|TBC\n|TBC\n|TBC\n|TBC\n|TBC\n|-\n|}\n<small>Sources: [https://vfl.com.au/north-melbourne-womens-historical-data/ Club historical data] and [http://websites.sportstg.com/comp_info.cgi?c=1-118-0-518546-0&pool=1001&round=0&a=STATS VFLW stats]</small>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports|Australia}}\n* [[Sport in Australia]]\n* [[Sport in Victoria]]\n* [[List of North Melbourne Football Club players]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.kangaroos.com.au/ }}\n* [http://www.aroundthegrounds.bellestorie.com/arden/arden.html \"Around the Grounds\" \u2013 web documentary \u2013 Arden Street]\n* [http://www.footyjumpers.com/ Club Footy Jumpers]\n* [http://shawfactor.com/reference/history_of_North_melbourne_fc/ Shawfactor: History of North Melbourne FC]\n\n{{North Melbourne Football Club}}\n{{VFL/AFL minor premiers}}\n{{VFL/AFL premiers}}\n{{Australian Football League}}\n{{AFL Women's}}\n{{VFL}}\n{{Melbourne Sports Teams}}\n\n[[Category:North Melbourne Football Club]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1869]]\n[[Category:Australian Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:AFL Women's clubs]]\n[[Category:Australian rules football clubs in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:1869 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Former Victorian Football League clubs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian rules football club}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox Australian football club\n|color1 = #000099\n|color2 = white\n|color3 = solid white\n| clubname  = <small>North Melbourne Football Club</small>\n| image     = [[File:North Melbourne FC logo.svg|170px]]\n| fullname  = North Melbourne Football Club Ltd<ref>{{cite web |title=NORTH MELBOURNE FOOTBALL CLUB LIMITED |publisher=[[Australian Securities and Investments Commission|ASIC]] |url=http://www.search.asic.gov.au/cgi-bin/gns030c?acn=006_468_962&juris=9&hdtext=ACN&srchsrc=1}}</ref>\n| nicknames = ''Kangaroos, Roos, North, Kangas, Shinboners''\n| mottos     = [[List of mottos|Vic