{"title_page": "Elisabetta Fanton", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Elisabetta Fanton\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| fullname      = \n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1968|12|26|df=yes}} \n| birth_place   = [[Treviso]], Italy\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   =\n| discipline    =\n| role          =\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     =\n}}\n\n'''Elisabetta Fanton''' (born 26 December 1968) is an Italian former [[Cycle sport|cyclist]]. She competed in the [[Cycling at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's sprint|women's sprint event]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fa/elisabetta-fanton-1.html |title=Elisabetta Fanton Olympic Results |accessdate=10 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|29595}}\n\n{{Italian National Road Race Championships (women)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fanton, Elisabetta}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian female cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Treviso]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Elisabetta Fanton\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| fullname      = \n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1968|12|26|df=yes}} \n| birth_place   = [[Treviso]], Italy\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   =\n| discipline    =\n| role          =\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     =\n}}\n\n'''Elisabetta Fanton''' (born 26 December 1968) is an Italian former [[Cycle sport|cyclist]]. She competed in the [[Cycling at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's sprint|women's sprint event]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fa/elisabetta-fanton-1.html |title=Elisabetta Fanton Olympic Results |accessdate=10 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|29595}}\n\n{{Italian National Road Race Championships (women)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fanton, Elisabetta}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian female cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Treviso]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1960s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elisabetta_Fanton"}
{"title_page": "Koi No Yokan", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Koi No Yokan\n| type         = Studio\n| artist       = [[Deftones]]\n| cover        = Deftones \u2013 Koi No Yokan.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2012|11|12}}\n| recorded     = 2012\n| studio       = {{ubl|Paramount Studios, Los Angeles|Ameraycan Studios and Encore Studios, North Hollywood}}\n| genre        = * [[Alternative metal]]\n* [[shoegaze]]\n* [[dream pop]]\n* [[post-metal]]\n| length       = 51:50\n| label        = [[Reprise Records|Reprise]]\n| producer     = [[Nick Raskulinecz]]\n| prev_title   = [[Covers (Deftones album)|Covers]]\n| prev_year    = 2011\n| next_title   = [[Gore (album)|Gore]]\n| next_year    = 2016\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Koi No Yokan\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Leathers (Deftones song)|Leathers]]\n | single1date = September 19, 2012\n | single2     = [[Tempest (Deftones song)|Tempest]]\n | single2date = October 9, 2012\n | single3     = [[Swerve City]]\n | single3date = March 30, 2013\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Koi No Yokan''''' is the seventh [[studio album]] by American [[alternative metal]] band [[Deftones]], released on November 12, 2012 by [[Reprise Records]].<ref name=\"nme\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Alex Young|title=Deftones announce new album: Koi No Yokan| work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=August 30, 2012|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2012/08/deftones-announce-new-album-koi-no-yokan/|accessdate= September 19, 2012}}</ref> Its title is a phrase from Japanese language  \"\u604b\u306e\u4e88\u611f\", translating to \"premonition of love\".<ref name=\"globe\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/music/ruth-minnikins-new-album-invites-you-into-her-heart-and-hearth/article5364317/|title=Ruth Minnikin's new album invites you into her heart and hearth|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|last=Wheeler|first=Brad|date=November 16, 2012|accessdate=November 18, 2012|quote=Koi no Yokan is a Japanese phrase referring to the feeling, upon first meeting someone, that you will eventually fall in love. Though it might be facile to suggest that the phrase applies equally to the music on this album, it wouldn't be far from wrong. The Deftones have always had a way with instrumental sound, pulling elements from metal, alt-rock and shoegaze to create an emotionally evocative wall of guitars, but this time around the textures are even more closely tied to the songwriting. Perhaps that's why the songs seem more deeply engrossing, from the darkly churning textures of Gauze to the almost pop-flavoured melodies of Entombed. -J.D. Considine}}</ref><ref>Koi No Yokan (Japanese) - The sense upon first meeting a person that the two of you are going to fall in love. http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/39141780/theres-now-a-word-for-nails-on-a-blackboard---but-its-not-in-english</ref>\n\n''Koi No Yokan'' was met with widespread acclaim from critics upon its release, and debuted at number eleven on the [[Billboard 200|US ''Billboard'' 200]], selling over 65,000 copies in its first week of sales. According to [[Nielsen SoundScan]], it has sold over 200,000 copies to date in the United States.\n\n==Background==\nBand frontman [[Chino Moreno]] characterized the album as \"dynamic\" with a full range of noise, noting an increased contribution of ideas by bassist [[Sergio Vega (bassist)|Sergio Vega]] compared to their previous record, ''[[Diamond Eyes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Gary Graff|title=Deftones Racing Through Next Album, Hoping for October Release| work=[[Billboard.com]]|date=July 2, 2012|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/482268/deftones-racing-through-next-album-hoping-for-october-release|accessdate= September 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA major change in the recording process came with the use of the Fractal Audio Systems Axe-Fx [[preamplifier|preamp]]/effects processor, which creates the sound of multiple outboard amps and pedals and allowed for different tones. Vega said the group was able to \"bring Fractal into hotel rooms and run it into software and record ideas and flesh them out later\". The group tracked guitar, bass and vocals, then recorded drums and replaced the guitar, bass and vocals. Vega confirmed that \"everything was organic\".<ref name=\"Electronic Musician\">{{cite web|last=Micallef|first=Ken|title=Deftones - Modeling For Mayhem|url=http://www.emusician.com/artists/0767/deftones-%E2%80%93-modeling-for-mayhem/150662|work=Electronic Musician|publisher=New Bay Media|accessdate=April 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416180313/http://www.emusician.com/artists/0767/deftones-%E2%80%93-modeling-for-mayhem/150662|archive-date=April 16, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\nDescribed as having an \"alternative metal vibe\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/deftones-koi-no-yokan-album-review/|title=Deftones, 'Koi No Yokan' \u2013 Album Review|website=Loudwire|access-date=March 7, 2016|quote=Overall, if the Smashing Pumpkins were heavier, ballsier and angrier, they'd make albums that sound like this, since Deftones do have an alt-metal vibe. Moreno's lyrics are often from-the-journal-page and stream of thought, making them entirely open-ended and capable of attracting the disaffected.}}</ref> the music incorporates experimental elements from the band's previous albums ''[[Saturday Night Wrist]]'' (2006) and ''[[Diamond Eyes]]'' (2010),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=2953152|title=Deftones - Koi No Yokan [Album Review]|website=AbsolutePunk.net|access-date=March 7, 2016|quote=[...] the band is taking the experimental elements of Saturday Night Wrist and evolving it with the sound they created on Diamond Eyes. Unlike its predecessor however, this album has more of bassist Sergio Vega's handprints over it, as he and drummer Abe Cunningham's percussion skills give Koi No Yokan its backbone throughout. Carpenter will keep listeners guessing with the twists and tempo changes within his guitar work.}}</ref> incorporating elements from [[heavy metal music|metal]] (including [[doom metal]] and [[groove metal]]), [[alternative rock]], [[shoegaze]], [[dream pop]], [[post-rock]] and [[prog rock]].<ref name=\"globe\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2012/11/album-review-deftones-koi-no-yokan/|title=Album Review: Deftones \u2013 Koi No Yokan|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=March 7, 2016|quote=Koi No Yokan sees the Deftones fully embracing the shoegazer elements that were only experimented with on past albums [...] Opener \u201cSwerve City\u201d sways between delicate jangles (during verses) and dominating groove metal (during the chorus).}}</ref><ref name=\"Allmusicquoted\">{{cite web| last = Heaney| first = Gregory| title = Koi No Yokan| website= [[AllMusic]]|url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/koi-no-yokan-mw0002426695| accessdate = November 14, 2012|quote=In their continued exploration of the intersection of heaviness and harmony, Koi No Yokan finds the band returning with a warm, dreamy sound that feels more like heavy dream pop or shoegaze than light metal.}}</ref><ref name=sputnikfisher>{{cite web|last1=Fisher|first1=Greg|title=Deftones, Koi No Yokan|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/53428/Deftones-Koi-No-Yokan/|website=Sputnik Music|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"MetalInjection\">{{cite web|last=Rowe |first=Riley |url=http://www.metalinjection.net/reviews/deftones-gore |title=Gore \u2013 Deftones|work=Metal Injection|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Dean|title=Deftones - Koi No Yokan|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/165472-deftones-koi-no-yokan/|website=PopMatters|accessdate=3 June 2016|quote=\u201cTempest\u201d utilizes the capture-and-release found in post-rock/metal instrumentation[...]The mid-section of \u201cRosemary\u201d come as close to doom metal as Deftones have ever ventured}}</ref><ref name=\"rollingstone\"/><ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|last1=Dick|first1=Jonathan|title=Deftones' Chino Moreno On Surviving, Evolving And 'Gore'|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2016/05/03/476636845/deftones-chino-moreno-on-surviving-evolving-and-gore|website=npr.org|publisher=NPR|accessdate=3 June 2016|quote=From the trip-hop nuances of its self-titled album in 2003 to the bleak math metal tendencies of 2006's Saturday Night Wrist to the goth-rock tinged shoegaze of 2010's Diamond Eyes to the prog-rock flirting of 2012's Koi No Yokan, Deftones' catalogue reads like a case study in how a band can translate influences into a sound that's definitively their own.}}</ref>\n\n{{Listen|filename=Deftones_-_Rosemary.ogg|title=\"Rosemary\"|description=Sample of the ninth track \"Rosemary\", which was described by ''[[Slant (magazine)|Slant]]'' editor Michael Nordine to be \"as heavy as [it is] pretty, often at the same time: [Moreno] gently crooning over layers of slow-moving guitars.\"<ref name=\"slant-koi\" />|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n==Release==\nOn September 19, 2012, the band released the song \"[[Leathers (Deftones song)|Leathers]]\" as a promotional single via a free download on their website.<ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://www.guitarworld.com/deftones-premiere-new-song-leathers| title=Deftones Premiere New Song, \"Leathers\"|author=Josh Hart|magazine=[[Guitar World]]|date=September 20, 2012|accessdate= September 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.noisecreep.com/2012/09/19/deftones-leathers| title=Deftones, 'Leathers': Stream New Track, Download it for Free|author=Carlos Ramirez|website=[[Noisecreep]]|date=September 19, 2012|accessdate= September 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://loudwire.com/deftones-release-new-song-leathers-as-free-download-koi-no-yokan-track-listing/| title=Deftones Release New Song 'Leathers' as Free Download + 'Koi No Yokan' Track Listing|author=Graham \"Gruhamed\" Hartmann|magazine=[[Loudwire]]|date=September 19, 2012|accessdate= September 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/deftones_release_free_single_leathers| title=Deftones release free single, \"Leathers\"|author=Brian Kraus|magazine=[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]|date=September 19, 2012|accessdate= September 23, 2012}}</ref> On October 8, 2012, \"Leathers\" was released as the album's first single.<ref name=\"itunes-leathers\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/leathers-single/id568299944|title=Leathers - Single - Deftones|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=October 8, 2012|accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref> \"Leathers\" was also released as a limited-edition [[cassingle]] with \"Rosemary\" as the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deftones.com/news/2012/10/16/leathers-rosemary-cas-single| title=\"Leathers\" & \"Rosemary\" Cas-Single|accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn October 3, 2012, the song \"[[Tempest (Deftones song)|Tempest]]\" premiered on [[PureVolume]] for streaming.<ref>{{cite web|title=WORLD EXCLUSIVE: Stream New Deftones Single \"Tempest\"|publisher=PureVolume|date=October 3, 2012|url=http://www.purevolume.com/news/deftones-new-single-tempest-koi-no-yokan-stream-premiere|accessdate=October 30, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425183250/http://www.purevolume.com/news/deftones-new-single-tempest-koi-no-yokan-stream-premiere|archive-date=April 25, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> \"Tempest\" was released as a single on October 9, 2012.<ref name=\"itunes-tempest\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/tempest/id567330630|title=Tempest - Single - Deftones|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=October 9, 2012|accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Koi No Yokan'' was released on vinyl in four versions: a standard retail version pressed on 140-gram black vinyl (3,000 units), a direct-to-consumer version on 180-gram black vinyl with foil-stamped numbered jackets (1,000 units), an international edition pressed on 180-gram vinyl and an exclusive edition sold through [[Hot Topic]] retailers pressed on 140-gram clear-colored vinyl (1,500 units).<ref name=BlabberMouth>{{cite web|title=Deftones To Release Vinyl Edition Of 'Koi No Yokan'|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/deftones-to-release-vinyl-edition-of-koi-no-yokan/|work=Blabbermouth|accessdate=April 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThis was also the first album released through [[HDtracks]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hdtracks.com/koi-no-yokan |title= Koi No Yokan {{!}} HDtracks |publisher=HDtracks |accessdate=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Tour==\nThe band launched a tour on October 9, 2012, which ended on November 21 in Los Angeles. The band played at venues with capacities between 1,000 and 4,000 with the goal being to allow fans to experience the music before the album was released.<ref>{{cite web|last=Zemler|first=Emily|title=So So Deftones|url=http://pdc-connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/83408817/so-so-deftones|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Media LLC|accessdate=April 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 86/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/koi-no-yokan/deftones|title=Koi No Yokan - Deftones|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AbsolutePunk]]\n| rev1score = 9/10<ref name=\"Absolut\">{{cite web|last=Beringer|first=Drew|title=Deftones - Koi No Yokan|website=[[AbsolutePunk]]|url= http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=2953152|date=November 15, 2012|accessdate=November 19, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web| last = Heaney| first = Gregory| title = Koi No Yokan| website= [[AllMusic]]|url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/koi-no-yokan-mw0002426695| accessdate = November 14, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[BBC Music]]\n| rev3score = favorable<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|last=Pearlman|first=Mischa|title=Deftones Koi No Yokan Review|publisher=[[BBC Music]]|work=[[BBC Online]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/gcq4|date=November 12, 2012|accessdate= November 18, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = [[Drowned in Sound]]\n| rev4score = 9/10<ref name=\"drowned\">{{cite magazine|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/17331/reviews/4145717|title=Deftones- Koi No Yokan |first=Michael|last=Brown |magazine=[[Drowned in Sound]]|date=November 9, 2012 |accessdate=November 9, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>Kerrang! magazine issue November 7, 2012</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Loudwire]]''\n| rev6score =  {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://loudwire.com/deftones-koi-no-yokan-album-review/|title=Deftones, 'Koi No Yokan' \u2013 Album Review|last=Sciaretto|first=Amy|magazine=[[Loudwire]]|accessdate=November 19, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev7score = 8/10<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite magazine|url=http://25.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_md4jvcpDXs1r3cz10o1_500.jpg |title=Koi No Yokan review |first=Al|last=Horner |magazine=[[NME]] |date=November 8, 2012 |accessdate=November 8, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[Slant Magazine]]\n| rev8Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"slant-koi\">{{cite web|last1=Nordine|first1=Michael|title=Deftones Koi No Yokan|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/deftones-koi-no-yokan|website=[[Slant (magazine)|Slant]]|accessdate=May 24, 2018|date=November 20, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9score = 7/10<ref name=\"spin\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/deftones-koi-no-yokan-reprise|title=Deftones, 'Koi No Yokan'|magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|first=Theon|last=Weber|date=November 16, 2012|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev10 = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| rev10score = 4.4/5<ref name=\"sputnik\">{{cite web|title=Review: Deftones - Koi No Yokan|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/53428/Deftones-Koi-No-Yokan/|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|first=Greg|last=Fisher|date=November 18, 2012|accessdate=November 22, 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe album was met with overall critical acclaim. The aggregate review site [[Metacritic]] assigned an average score of 86 to the album based on 18 reviews, indicating \"Universal Acclaim\".<ref name=\"MC\"/> With this score, ''Koi No Yokan'' was among the eight best-reviewed albums of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jason Dietz|title=The best albums of 2012| work=[[Metacritic]]|date=December 21, 2012|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-of-2012/|accessdate= January 4, 2013}}</ref> Gregory Heaney of [[AllMusic]] wrote, \"While a lot of bands out there have been tinkering with the loud/quiet dynamic for decades now, what makes Deftones so special is their ability to do both at the same time, effectively blending the calm and the storm into a single sound\".<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/> Mischa Pearlman of [[BBC Music]] wrote, \"It transcends the boundaries and expectations of its genre--even those previously set by the very band that made it\".<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Al Horner of ''[[NME]]'' said of the album, \"It's a shotgun blast of cranked guitars, bruising hardcore and canyon-sized choruses, and it's mesmerising\".<ref name=\"nme\"/> Greg Fisher of [[Sputnikmusic]] called it \"a remarkably consistent effort\" that \"glitters with supreme melodies as much as crushes with massive riffs showcasing the quintet's most accomplished material in over a decade\".<ref name=\"sputnik\"/> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called the album \"adventurously aggressive\" and stated, \"Koi No Yokan ranges from brutal, blunt-force trauma ('Gauze') to epic prog-rock atmospherics (the sprawling, enchanting 'Tempest'). Opener 'Swerve City' sets the tone immediately with a bludgeoning riff, but Deftones also take nuanced approaches to angsty tension, weaving meticulously crafted cosmic rock on 'Entombed' and wading through murky, jagged textures on 'Rosemary'\".<ref name=\"rollingstone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/deftones-unleash-angst-and-tension-in-new-album-koi-no-yokan-premiere-20121108|title=Deftones Unleash Angst and Tension in New Album 'Koi No Yokan' - Premiere|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' named ''Koi No Yokan'' the \"Album of the Year\" at the fifth annual Revolver Golden Gods Award Show.<ref>{{cite web|author=Zach Shaw|title=And The Winners of the Revolver Golden Gods Awards 2013 Are\u2026| work=[[Metal Insider]]|date=May 3, 2013|url=http://www.metalinsider.net/award-show-battles/and-the-winners-of-the-revolver-golden-gods-awards-2013-are/|accessdate= May 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe album debuted at No. 11 on ''Billboard'' 200, and No. 5 on the Top Rock Albums,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/rock-albums/2012-12-01 |title=Rock Albums |date=December 1, 2012 |work=Billboard }}</ref> selling 65,000 copies in the first week.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/deftones_koi_no_yokan_cracks_us_top_15.html |title=Deftones' 'Koi No Yokan' Cracks U.S. Top 15|date= November 25, 2012|work=Ultimate Guitar }}</ref> The album has sold 214,000 copies in the US as of March 2016.<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304023201/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archivedate= March 4, 2016 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |website=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS Digital Ventures }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|all_lyrics = [[Chino Moreno]]\n|all_music  = [[Deftones]]\n|title1     = [[Swerve City]]\n|length1    = 2:44\n|title2     = Romantic Dreams\n|length2    = 4:38\n|title3     = [[Leathers (Deftones song)|Leathers]]\n|length3    = 4:08\n|title4     = Poltergeist\n|length4    = 3:31\n|title5     = Entombed\n|length5    = 4:59\n|title6     = Graphic Nature\n|length6    = 4:32\n|title7     = [[Tempest (Deftones song)|Tempest]]\n|length7    = 6:05\n|title8     = Gauze\n|length8    = 4:41\n|title9     = Rosemary\n|length9    = 6:53\n|title10    = Goon Squad\n|length10   = 5:40\n|title11    = What Happened to You?\n|length11   = 3:53\n|total_length = 51:50\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\nAdapted from the CD liner notes.<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=Koi No Yokan |others=Deftones |date=2012 |url= |last= |first= |pages= |type=CD liner |publisher=[[Reprise Records]] |id= |location= }}</ref>\n\n'''Deftones'''\n* [[Abe Cunningham]] \u2212 drums\n* [[Stephen Carpenter]] \u2212 guitar\n* [[Frank Delgado (American musician)|Frank Delgado]] \u2212 [[Sampling (music)|samples]], keyboards\n* [[Chino Moreno]] \u2212 vocals, guitar\n* [[Sergio Vega (bassist)|Sergio Vega]] \u2212 bass\n\n'''Technical'''\n* [[Nick Raskulinecz]] \u2212 [[Record producer|production]]\n* [[Matt Hyde]] \u2212 production, [[Audio engineering|engineering]]\n* Steve Olmon \u2212 engineering\n* [[Rich Costey]] \u2212 [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n* Eric Isip \u2212 mixing\n* [[Ted Jensen]] \u2212 [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n* Chris Kasych \u2212 [[Pro Tools|protools mix engineering]]\n* Frank Maddocks \u2212 [[art direction]], package design\n* Futura \u2212 photography\n* 13th Witness \u2212 band photograph\n\n== Charts ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (2012)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Canadian Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"billboard charts\">{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=deftones|chart=all}}|title=Koi No Yokan - Deftones|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=November 22, 2012}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[MAHASZ|Hungarian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahasz.hu/?menu=slagerlistak&menu2=archivum&lista=top40&ev=2012&het=46&submit_=Keres%E9s|title=MAHASZ \u2013 Magyar Hanglemezkiad\u00f3k Sz\u00f6vets\u00e9ge |publisher=mahasz.hu |accessdate=November 27, 2012}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|40\n|-\n{{albumchart |Germany|17 |artist=Deftones |rowheader=yes}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[UK Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"UKcharts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/deftones/|title=Deftones - UK Chart History|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=November 22, 2012}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Billboard 200|U.S. ''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"billboard charts\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|U.S. Rock Albums<ref name=\"billboard charts\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|U.S. Alternative Albums<ref name=\"billboard charts\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|U.S. Hard Rock Albums<ref name=\"billboard charts\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Chart\n!Position\n|-\n|2013\n|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]\n|align=\"center\"|174<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2013/the-billboard-200?page=17|title=Billboard|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Deftones}}\n\n[[Category:2012 albums]]\n[[Category:Deftones albums]]\n[[Category:Reprise Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Nick Raskulinecz]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Koi No Yokan\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Deftones]]\n| cover      = Deftones \u2013 Koi No Yokan.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2012|11|12}}\n| recorded   = 2012\n| studio     = {{ubl|Paramount Studios, Los Angeles|Ameraycan Studios and Encore Studios, North Hollywood}}\n| genre      = [[Alternative metal]]\n| length     = 51:50\n| label      = [[Reprise Records|Reprise]]\n| producer   = [[Nick Raskulinecz]]\n| prev_title = [[Covers (Deftones album)|Covers]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[Gore (album)|Gore]]\n| next_year  = 2016\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Koi No Yokan\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Leathers (Deftones song)|Leathers]]\n | single1date = September 19, 2012\n | single2     = [[Tempest (Deftones song)|Tempest]]\n | single2date = October 9, 2012\n | single3     = [[Swerve City]]\n | single3date = March 30, 2013\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Koi No Yokan''''' is the seventh [[studio album]] by American [[alternative metal]] band [[Deftones]], released on November 12, 2012 by [[Reprise Records]].<ref name=\"nme\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Alex Young|title=Deftones announce new album: Koi No Yokan| work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=August 30, 2012|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2012/08/deftones-announce-new-album-koi-no-yokan/|accessdate= September 19, 2012}}</ref> Its title is a phrase from Japanese language  \"\u604b\u306e\u4e88\u611f\", translating to \"premonition of love\".<ref name=\"globe\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/music/ruth-minnikins-new-album-invites-you-into-her-heart-and-hearth/article5364317/|title=Ruth Minnikin's new album invites you into her heart and hearth|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|last=Wheeler|first=Brad|date=November 16, 2012|accessdate=November 18, 2012|quote=Koi no Yokan is a Japanese phrase referring to the feeling, upon first meeting someone, that you will eventually fall in love. Though it might be facile to suggest that the phrase applies equally to the music on this album, it wouldn't be far from wrong. The Deftones have always had a way with instrumental sound, pulling elements from metal, alt-rock and shoegaze to create an emotionally evocative wall of guitars, but this time around the textures are even more closely tied to the songwriting. Perhaps that's why the songs seem more deeply engrossing, from the darkly churning textures of Gauze to the almost pop-flavoured melodies of Entombed. -J.D. Considine}}</ref><ref>Koi No Yokan (Japanese) - The sense upon first meeting a person that the two of you are going to fall in love. http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/39141780/theres-now-a-word-for-nails-on-a-blackboard---but-its-not-in-english</ref>\n\n''Koi No Yokan'' was met with widespread acclaim from critics upon its release, and debuted at number eleven on the [[Billboard 200|US ''Billboard'' 200]], selling over 65,000 copies in its first week of sales. According to [[Nielsen SoundScan]], it has sold over 200,000 copies to date in the United States.\n\n==Background==\nBand frontman [[Chino Moreno]] characterized the album as \"dynamic\" with a full range of noise, noting an increased contribution of ideas by bassist [[Sergio Vega (bassist)|Sergio Vega]] compared to their previous record, ''[[Diamond Eyes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Gary Graff|title=Deftones Racing Through Next Album, Hoping for October Release| work=[[Billboard.com]]|date=July 2, 2012|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/482268/deftones-racing-through-next-album-hoping-for-october-release|accessdate= September 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA major change in the recording process came with the use of the Fractal Audio Systems Axe-Fx [[preamplifier|preamp]]/effects processor, which creates the sound of multiple outboard amps and pedals and allowed for different tones. Vega said the group was able to \"bring Fractal into hotel rooms and run it into software and record ideas and flesh them out later\". The group tracked guitar, bass and vocals, then recorded drums and replaced the guitar, bass and vocals. Vega confirmed that \"everything was organic\".<ref name=\"Electronic Musician\">{{cite web|last=Micallef|first=Ken|title=Deftones - Modeling For Mayhem|url=http://www.emusician.com/artists/0767/deftones-%E2%80%93-modeling-for-mayhem/150662|work=Electronic Musician|publisher=New Bay Media|accessdate=April 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416180313/http://www.emusician.com/artists/0767/deftones-%E2%80%93-modeling-for-mayhem/150662|archive-date=April 16, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\nDescribed as having an \"alternative metal vibe\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/deftones-koi-no-yokan-album-review/|title=Deftones, 'Koi No Yokan' \u2013 Album Review|website=Loudwire|access-date=March 7, 2016|quote=Overall, if the Smashing Pumpkins were heavier, ballsier and angrier, they'd make albums that sound like this, since Deftones do have an alt-metal vibe. Moreno's lyrics are often from-the-journal-page and stream of thought, making them entirely open-ended and capable of attracting the disaffected.}}</ref> the music incorporates experimental elements from the band's previous albums ''[[Saturday Night Wrist]]'' (2006) and ''[[Diamond Eyes]]'' (2010),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=2953152|title=Deftones - Koi No Yokan [Album Review]|website=AbsolutePunk.net|access-date=March 7, 2016|quote=[...] the band is taking the experimental elements of Saturday Night Wrist and evolving it with the sound they created on Diamond Eyes. Unlike its predecessor however, this album has more of bassist Sergio Vega's handprints over it, as he and drummer Abe Cunningham's percussion skills give Koi No Yokan its backbone throughout. Carpenter will keep listeners guessing with the twists and tempo changes within his guitar work.}}</ref> incorporating elements from [[heavy metal music|metal]] (including [[doom metal]] and [[groove metal]]), [[alternative rock]], [[shoegaze]], [[dream pop]], [[post-rock]] and [[prog rock]].<ref name=\"globe\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2012/11/album-review-deftones-koi-no-yokan/|title=Album Review: Deftones \u2013 Koi No Yokan|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=March 7, 2016|quote=Koi No Yokan sees the Deftones fully embracing the shoegazer elements that were only experimented with on past albums [...] Opener \u201cSwerve City\u201d sways between delicate jangles (during verses) and dominating groove metal (during the chorus).}}</ref><ref name=\"Allmusicquoted\">{{cite web| last = Heaney| first = Gregory| title = Koi No Yokan| website= [[AllMusic]]|url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/koi-no-yokan-mw0002426695| accessdate = November 14, 2012|quote=In their continued exploration of the intersection of heaviness and harmony, Koi No Yokan finds the band returning with a warm, dreamy sound that feels more like heavy dream pop or shoegaze than light metal.}}</ref><ref name=sputnikfisher>{{cite web|last1=Fisher|first1=Greg|title=Deftones, Koi No Yokan|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/53428/Deftones-Koi-No-Yokan/|website=Sputnik Music|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"MetalInjection\">{{cite web|last=Rowe |first=Riley |url=http://www.metalinjection.net/reviews/deftones-gore |title=Gore \u2013 Deftones|work=Metal Injection|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Dean|title=Deftones - Koi No Yokan|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/165472-deftones-koi-no-yokan/|website=PopMatters|accessdate=3 June 2016|quote=\u201cTempest\u201d utilizes the capture-and-release found in post-rock/metal instrumentation[...]The mid-section of \u201cRosemary\u201d come as close to doom metal as Deftones have ever ventured}}</ref><ref name=\"rollingstone\"/><ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|last1=Dick|first1=Jonathan|title=Deftones' Chino Moreno On Surviving, Evolving And 'Gore'|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2016/05/03/476636845/deftones-chino-moreno-on-surviving-evolving-and-gore|website=npr.org|publisher=NPR|accessdate=3 June 2016|quote=From the trip-hop nuances of its self-titled album in 2003 to the bleak math metal tendencies of 2006's Saturday Night Wrist to the goth-rock tinged shoegaze of 2010's Diamond Eyes to the prog-rock flirting of 2012's Koi No Yokan, Deftones' catalogue reads like a case study in how a band can translate influences into a sound that's definitively their own.}}</ref>\n\n{{Listen|filename=Deftones_-_Rosemary.ogg|title=\"Rosemary\"|description=Sample of the ninth track \"Rosemary\", which was described by ''[[Slant (magazine)|Slant]]'' editor Michael Nordine to be \"as heavy as [it is] pretty, often at the same time: [Moreno] gently crooning over layers of slow-moving guitars.\"<ref name=\"slant-koi\" />|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n==Release==\nOn September 19, 2012, the band released the song \"[[Leathers (Deftones song)|Leathers]]\" as a promotional single via a free download on their website.<ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://www.guitarworld.com/deftones-premiere-new-song-leathers| title=Deftones Premiere New Song, \"Leathers\"|author=Josh Hart|magazine=[[Guitar World]]|date=September 20, 2012|accessdate= September 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.noisecreep.com/2012/09/19/deftones-leathers| title=Deftones, 'Leathers': Stream New Track, Download it for Free|author=Carlos Ramirez|website=[[Noisecreep]]|date=September 19, 2012|accessdate= September 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://loudwire.com/deftones-release-new-song-leathers-as-free-download-koi-no-yokan-track-listing/| title=Deftones Release New Song 'Leathers' as Free Download + 'Koi No Yokan' Track Listing|author=Graham \"Gruhamed\" Hartmann|magazine=[[Loudwire]]|date=September 19, 2012|accessdate= September 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/deftones_release_free_single_leathers| title=Deftones release free single, \"Leathers\"|author=Brian Kraus|magazine=[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]|date=September 19, 2012|accessdate= September 23, 2012}}</ref> On October 8, 2012, \"Leathers\" was released as the album's first single.<ref name=\"itunes-leathers\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/leathers-single/id568299944|title=Leathers - Single - Deftones|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=October 8, 2012|accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref> \"Leathers\" was also released as a limited-edition [[cassingle]] with \"Rosemary\" as the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deftones.com/news/2012/10/16/leathers-rosemary-cas-single| title=\"Leathers\" & \"Rosemary\" Cas-Single|accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn October 3, 2012, the song \"[[Tempest (Deftones song)|Tempest]]\" premiered on [[PureVolume]] for streaming.<ref>{{cite web|title=WORLD EXCLUSIVE: Stream New Deftones Single \"Tempest\"|publisher=PureVolume|date=October 3, 2012|url=http://www.purevolume.com/news/deftones-new-single-tempest-koi-no-yokan-stream-premiere|accessdate=October 30, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425183250/http://www.purevolume.com/news/deftones-new-single-tempest-koi-no-yokan-stream-premiere|archive-date=April 25, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> \"Tempest\" was released as a single on October 9, 2012.<ref name=\"itunes-tempest\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/tempest/id567330630|title=Tempest - Single - Deftones|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=October 9, 2012|accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Koi No Yokan'' was released on vinyl in four versions: a standard retail version pressed on 140-gram black vinyl (3,000 units), a direct-to-consumer version on 180-gram black vinyl with foil-stamped numbered jackets (1,000 units), an international edition pressed on 180-gram vinyl and an exclusive edition sold through [[Hot Topic]] retailers pressed on 140-gram clear-colored vinyl (1,500 units).<ref name=BlabberMouth>{{cite web|title=Deftones To Release Vinyl Edition Of 'Koi No Yokan'|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/deftones-to-release-vinyl-edition-of-koi-no-yokan/|work=Blabbermouth|accessdate=April 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThis was also the first album released through [[HDtracks]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hdtracks.com/koi-no-yokan |title= Koi No Yokan {{!}} HDtracks |publisher=HDtracks |accessdate=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Tour==\nThe band launched a tour on October 9, 2012, which ended on November 21 in Los Angeles. The band played at venues with capacities between 1,000 and 4,000 with the goal being to allow fans to experience the music before the album was released.<ref>{{cite web|last=Zemler|first=Emily|title=So So Deftones|url=http://pdc-connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/83408817/so-so-deftones|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Media LLC|accessdate=April 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 86/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/koi-no-yokan/deftones|title=Koi No Yokan - Deftones|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AbsolutePunk]]\n| rev1score = 9/10<ref name=\"Absolut\">{{cite web|last=Beringer|first=Drew|title=Deftones - Koi No Yokan|website=[[AbsolutePunk]]|url= http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=2953152|date=November 15, 2012|accessdate=November 19, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web| last = Heaney| first = Gregory| title = Koi No Yokan| website= [[AllMusic]]|url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/koi-no-yokan-mw0002426695| accessdate = November 14, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[BBC Music]]\n| rev3score = favorable<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|last=Pearlman|first=Mischa|title=Deftones Koi No Yokan Review|publisher=[[BBC Music]]|work=[[BBC Online]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/gcq4|date=November 12, 2012|accessdate= November 18, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = [[Drowned in Sound]]\n| rev4score = 9/10<ref name=\"drowned\">{{cite magazine|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/17331/reviews/4145717|title=Deftones- Koi No Yokan |first=Michael|last=Brown |magazine=[[Drowned in Sound]]|date=November 9, 2012 |accessdate=November 9, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>Kerrang! magazine issue November 7, 2012</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Loudwire]]''\n| rev6score =  {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://loudwire.com/deftones-koi-no-yokan-album-review/|title=Deftones, 'Koi No Yokan' \u2013 Album Review|last=Sciaretto|first=Amy|magazine=[[Loudwire]]|accessdate=November 19, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev7score = 8/10<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite magazine|url=http://25.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_md4jvcpDXs1r3cz10o1_500.jpg |title=Koi No Yokan review |first=Al|last=Horner |magazine=[[NME]] |date=November 8, 2012 |accessdate=November 8, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[Slant Magazine]]\n| rev8Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"slant-koi\">{{cite web|last1=Nordine|first1=Michael|title=Deftones Koi No Yokan|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/deftones-koi-no-yokan|website=[[Slant (magazine)|Slant]]|accessdate=May 24, 2018|date=November 20, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9score = 7/10<ref name=\"spin\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/deftones-koi-no-yokan-reprise|title=Deftones, 'Koi No Yokan'|magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|first=Theon|last=Weber|date=November 16, 2012|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev10 = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| rev10score = 4.4/5<ref name=\"sputnik\">{{cite web|title=Review: Deftones - Koi No Yokan|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/53428/Deftones-Koi-No-Yokan/|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|first=Greg|last=Fisher|date=November 18, 2012|accessdate=November 22, 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe album was met with overall critical acclaim. The aggregate review site [[Metacritic]] assigned an average score of 86 to the album based on 18 reviews, indicating \"Universal Acclaim\".<ref name=\"MC\"/> With this score, ''Koi No Yokan'' was among the eight best-reviewed albums of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jason Dietz|title=The best albums of 2012| work=[[Metacritic]]|date=December 21, 2012|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-of-2012/|accessdate= January 4, 2013}}</ref> Gregory Heaney of [[AllMusic]] wrote, \"While a lot of bands out there have been tinkering with the loud/quiet dynamic for decades now, what makes Deftones so special is their ability to do both at the same time, effectively blending the calm and the storm into a single sound\".<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/> Mischa Pearlman of [[BBC Music]] wrote, \"It transcends the boundaries and expectations of its genre--even those previously set by the very band that made it\".<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Al Horner of ''[[NME]]'' said of the album, \"It's a shotgun blast of cranked guitars, bruising hardcore and canyon-sized choruses, and it's mesmerising\".<ref name=\"nme\"/> Greg Fisher of [[Sputnikmusic]] called it \"a remarkably consistent effort\" that \"glitters with supreme melodies as much as crushes with massive riffs showcasing the quintet's most accomplished material in over a decade\".<ref name=\"sputnik\"/> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called the album \"adventurously aggressive\" and stated, \"Koi No Yokan ranges from brutal, blunt-force trauma ('Gauze') to epic prog-rock atmospherics (the sprawling, enchanting 'Tempest'). Opener 'Swerve City' sets the tone immediately with a bludgeoning riff, but Deftones also take nuanced approaches to angsty tension, weaving meticulously crafted cosmic rock on 'Entombed' and wading through murky, jagged textures on 'Rosemary'\".<ref name=\"rollingstone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/deftones-unleash-angst-and-tension-in-new-album-koi-no-yokan-premiere-20121108|title=Deftones Unleash Angst and Tension in New Album 'Koi No Yokan' - Premiere|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' named ''Koi No Yokan'' the \"Album of the Year\" at the fifth annual Revolver Golden Gods Award Show.<ref>{{cite web|author=Zach Shaw|title=And The Winners of the Revolver Golden Gods Awards 2013 Are\u2026| work=[[Metal Insider]]|date=May 3, 2013|url=http://www.metalinsider.net/award-show-battles/and-the-winners-of-the-revolver-golden-gods-awards-2013-are/|accessdate= May 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe album debuted at No. 11 on ''Billboard'' 200, and No. 5 on the Top Rock Albums,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/rock-albums/2012-12-01 |title=Rock Albums |date=December 1, 2012 |work=Billboard }}</ref> selling 65,000 copies in the first week.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/deftones_koi_no_yokan_cracks_us_top_15.html |title=Deftones' 'Koi No Yokan' Cracks U.S. Top 15|date= November 25, 2012|work=Ultimate Guitar }}</ref> The album has sold 214,000 copies in the US as of March 2016.<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304023201/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archivedate= March 4, 2016 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |website=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS Digital Ventures }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|all_lyrics = [[Chino Moreno]]\n|all_music  = [[Deftones]]\n|title1     = [[Swerve City]]\n|length1    = 2:44\n|title2     = Romantic Dreams\n|length2    = 4:38\n|title3     = [[Leathers (Deftones song)|Leathers]]\n|length3    = 4:08\n|title4     = Poltergeist\n|length4    = 3:31\n|title5     = Entombed\n|length5    = 4:59\n|title6     = Graphic Nature\n|length6    = 4:32\n|title7     = [[Tempest (Deftones song)|Tempest]]\n|length7    = 6:05\n|title8     = Gauze\n|length8    = 4:41\n|title9     = Rosemary\n|length9    = 6:53\n|title10    = Goon Squad\n|length10   = 5:40\n|title11    = What Happened to You?\n|length11   = 3:53\n|total_length = 51:50\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\nAdapted from the CD liner notes.<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=Koi No Yokan |others=Deftones |date=2012 |url= |last= |first= |pages= |type=CD liner |publisher=[[Reprise Records]] |id= |location= }}</ref>\n\n'''Deftones'''\n* [[Abe Cunningham]] \u2212 drums\n* [[Stephen Carpenter]] \u2212 guitar\n* [[Frank Delgado (American musician)|Frank Delgado]] \u2212 [[Sampling (music)|samples]], keyboards\n* [[Chino Moreno]] \u2212 vocals, guitar\n* [[Sergio Vega (bassist)|Sergio Vega]] \u2212 bass\n\n'''Technical'''\n* [[Nick Raskulinecz]] \u2212 [[Record producer|production]]\n* [[Matt Hyde]] \u2212 production, [[Audio engineering|engineering]]\n* Steve Olmon \u2212 engineering\n* [[Rich Costey]] \u2212 [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n* Eric Isip \u2212 mixing\n* [[Ted Jensen]] \u2212 [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n* Chris Kasych \u2212 [[Pro Tools|protools mix engineering]]\n* Frank Maddocks \u2212 [[art direction]], package design\n* Futura \u2212 photography\n* 13th Witness \u2212 band photograph\n\n== Charts ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (2012)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Canadian Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"billboard charts\">{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=deftones|chart=all}}|title=Koi No Yokan - Deftones|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=November 22, 2012}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[MAHASZ|Hungarian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahasz.hu/?menu=slagerlistak&menu2=archivum&lista=top40&ev=2012&het=46&submit_=Keres%E9s|title=MAHASZ \u2013 Magyar Hanglemezkiad\u00f3k Sz\u00f6vets\u00e9ge |publisher=mahasz.hu |accessdate=November 27, 2012}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|40\n|-\n{{albumchart |Germany|17 |artist=Deftones |rowheader=yes}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[UK Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"UKcharts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/deftones/|title=Deftones - UK Chart History|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=November 22, 2012}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Billboard 200|U.S. ''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"billboard charts\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|U.S. Rock Albums<ref name=\"billboard charts\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|U.S. Alternative Albums<ref name=\"billboard charts\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|U.S. Hard Rock Albums<ref name=\"billboard charts\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Chart\n!Position\n|-\n|2013\n|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]\n|align=\"center\"|174<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2013/the-billboard-200?page=17|title=Billboard|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Deftones}}\n\n[[Category:2012 albums]]\n[[Category:Deftones albums]]\n[[Category:Reprise Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Nick Raskulinecz]]\n", "name_user": "HWT2103", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Koi_No_Yokan"}
{"title_page": "Suki Chan", "text_new": "{{blp sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Artist}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Suki Chan\n| image         = Suki Chan.jpg\n| image_size    = 220\n| caption       = Suki Chan filming Still Point in 2011\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = [[Hong Kong]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| field         = [[Video art]]<br>[[Installation Art]]<br>[[New Media Art]]\n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = ''MEMORY'' (2019),''Lucida'' (2016), ''Still Point'' (2012), ''Sleep Walk Sleep Talk'' (2010), ''Interval II'' (2008)\n| patrons       = \n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n}}\n\n'''Suki Chan''' (born 1977 in [[Hong Kong]]) is an artist and filmmaker whose work uses light, moving image and sound to explore our perception of reality.<ref name=\"tandfonline\">\n{{cite journal\n|title=Suki Chan: The Space Between| doi=10.1080/09528822.2010.502784\n|volume=24\n| issue=5\n|journal=Third Text\n|pages=635\u2013637 |year = 2010|last1 = Kember|first1 = Pamela}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"whitechapelgallery\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.whitechapelgallery.org/shop/product/category_id/183/product_id/1613?session_id=13950876885c2356b81665959d8c35b4155fdfa1a2\n|title=Double Act: Becca Voelcker; Suki Chan\n|publisher=whitechapelgallery.org\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"google\">\n{{cite book\n|title=Contemporary Visual Arts\n|author=Patrick, K.\n|date=2000\n|issue=nos. 28\u201331\n|publisher=G+B Magazines Unlimited\n|issn=1028-5040\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SHZMAAAAYAAJ|isbn=9783908247999\n}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"greenroomutd\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.greenroomutd.org/people/suki-chan\n|title=Suki Chan &#124; www.greenroomutd.org\n|publisher=greenroomutd.org\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref> She is drawn to light as a physical phenomenon, and the role it plays in our constantly shifting daily experience of our environment, be it urban or rural.<ref name=\"artangel\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.artangel.org.uk/about_us/open/open_100/suki_chan|title=Artangel &#124;\n|publisher=artangel.org.uk|accessdate=2014-09-22}} \n</ref> Her pieces vary from photography, film installation to mixed-media sculptures.<ref name=\"a-n\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.a-n.co.uk/artists_talking/artists_stories/single/377223\n|title=Suki Chan &laquo; a-n The Artists Information Company|publisher=a-n.co.uk\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"culturehall\">\n{{cite web|url=http://culturehall.com/suki_chan/biography;jsessionid=5E58FB50DEA085E97B7E1B2DE6C59F30|title=Suki Chan - Artist Biography and CV\n|publisher=culturehall.com|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref>\n\nChan is based in London and is represented by Tintype Gallery.<ref name=\"tintypegallery\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tintypegallery.com/artists/suki-chan/|title=Suki Chan|publisher=tintypegallery.com|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref> She is also a visiting lecturer at the Royal College of Art.\n\n==Education==\n1996: Foundation in Art and Design- Winchester School of Art\n\n1999: BA Fine Art- Goldsmiths\n\n2008: MA Fine Art Chelsea\n\n==Commissions==\nChan has been commissioned by various organisations to produce work for both galleries and public spaces; including [[Science Gallery Dublin]], <ref name=\"science-gallery-dublin\">{{cite web|url=https://dublin.sciencegallery.com/seeing|title=SEEING|publisher=Science Gallery|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> Film and Video Umbrella,<ref name=\"fvu\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.fvu.co.uk/projects/detail/artists/suki-chan\n|title=Suki Chan &#124; Commissions &#124; Projects &#124; \n|publisher=Film and Video Umbrella\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref> [[Centre for Chinese Contemporary Art]],<ref name=\"CFCCA archive\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://archive.cfcca.org.uk/index.php/Detail/entities/88\n|title= CFCCA Archive: Person: Chan, Suki, artist, (b.1977)\n|publisher=[[Centre for Chinese Contemporary Art]]\n|accessdate=2018-11-11}}\n</ref> The Young Foundation, [[Art on the Underground]] <ref name=\"tfl\">{{cite web|url=http://art.tfl.gov.uk/projects/current/artist/9220|title=Art on the Underground - Current Projects|publisher=art.tfl.gov.uk|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref> and [[Aspex Gallery]].<ref name=\"whitechapelgallery\"/><ref name=\"google3\">{{cite book|title=A Hundred Seas Rising|author1=Chan, S.|author2=Bushnell, J.|date=2012|publisher=Aspex|isbn=9780955025846|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_3q6kQEACAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nChan\u2019s work is included in the collections of the [[Museum of London]],<ref name=\"museumoflondon\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/corporate/press-media/press-releases/sleep-walk-sleep-talk/\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131122094048/http://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/corporate/press-media/press-releases/sleep-walk-sleep-talk/\n|archive-date=2013-11-22\n|url-status=dead\n|title=Sleep walk sleep talk\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref> [[University of Salford]] Arts Collection,<ref name=\"salford art collection\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://artcollection.salford.ac.uk/chinese-contemporary-art/\n|title=New Collection of Chinese Contemporary Art\n|publisher=[[University of Salford]]\n|accessdate=2018-11-11}}</ref> [[University of the Arts London|University of the Arts]] Art Collection, [[David Roberts Art Foundation]] and the [[Ingram Collection of Modern British Art|Ingram Collection]].<ref name=\"ingramcollection\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.ingramcollection.com/artists/suki-chan\n|title=Suki Chan &laquo; The Ingram Collection of Modern British Art\n|publisher=ingramcollection.com\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2008, she was nominated for the Northern Art Prize<ref name=\"northernartprize\">{{cite web|url=http://www.northernartprize.org.uk/2008-prize|title=2008 Prize Northern Art Prize|publisher=northernartprize.org.uk|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref><ref name=\"a-n2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.a-n.co.uk/artists_talking/article/458239|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319044140/http://www.a-n.co.uk/artists_talking/article/458239 |archive-date=2014-03-19 |url-status=dead|title=Northern Art Prize 2008 &#124; Artists talking &#124; a-n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref> and in 2010, she was shortlisted for the Renaissance Art Prize.<ref name=\"esteri\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icilondon.esteri.it/IIC_Londra/webform/SchedaEvento.aspx?id=554|title=Italian Cultural Institute London|publisher=icilondon.esteri.it|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Chan was one of the 6 young British artists featured in the BBC\u2019s series [[School of Saatchi]].<ref name=\"saatchiart\">{{cite web|url=http://magazine.saatchiart.com/articles/artnews/london-solo-show-for-bbc-school-of-saatchi-finalist-suki-chan|title=London Solo Show for BBC School of Saatchi Finalist Suki Chan : Saatchi Art Magazine : News and Updates for Art Lovers|publisher=magazine.saatchiart.com|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref><ref name=\"thebookoftravels\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebookoftravels.org/acknowledgements/suki-chan|title=Suki Chan &#124; The Book of Travels|publisher=thebookoftravels.org|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref> On the show, [[Tracey Emin]] who said that her work was better than some established artists. \"The film's flipping brilliant,\" she said. \"There's a few artists' names come to mind when I saw it but this knocks spots off them.\"<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/art-news/6624377/Charles-Saatchi-hunts-for-new-star-on-artists-answer-to-X-Factor.html|title=Charles Saatchi hunts for new star on artists' answer to X Factor - Telegraph|publisher=telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref> Chan\u2019s work also received a positive review in The Guardian newspaper from the art critic Robert Clark who wrote \u201cSuki Chan\u2019s art makes us wonder in more ways than one. It enables us to treasure the wonder of the world through daring to suggest the dreadful cost of the loss of such wonderful phenomena.\u201d<ref name=\"thebookoftravels\"/><ref name=\"saatchionline\">{{cite web|url=http://ap.saatchionline.com/art/Photography-Sleep-Walk-Sleep-Talk-film-still/11145/1434865/view|title=Saatchi Art Artist: Suki Chan; Color 2009 Photography \"Sleep Walk Sleep Talk, film still\"|publisher=ap.saatchionline.com|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref>\n\n==Residencies==\nIn partnership with Bluecoat and [[Arts Council England]], Chan was invited to be one of the artists in residence at the Belong care village, Crewe. Chan interviewed residents which formed the basis of her project, CONSCIOUS.<ref name=\"guardian_residency\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/jun/26/arts-care-homes-healthy|title='It helps residents stay healthy': the benefits of arts in care homes|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Bluecoat_residency\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebluecoat.org.uk/content/-suki-chan|title='Suki Chan, Feb 19|publisher=Bluecoat|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Arts_Council_Conscious\">{{cite web|url=https://www.artscouncil.org.uk/long-read/conscious|title=CONSCIOUS Suki Chan|publisher=Arts Council England|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Chan completed a residency at the Osteopathic Centre for Children, producing 1,000 origami cranes for their permanent installation at the charity's Manchester base.<ref name=\"Manchester_Evening_News_Residency\">{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/hatton-helps-launch-kids-project-1077141|title=Hatton helps launch kids' project|publisher=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian_Residency_2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/jan/26/northerner.martinwainwright|title=\nStop the tramlines, I want them cut off|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sukichan.co.uk/ Official website]\n*[http://archive.cfcca.org.uk/index.php/Detail/entities/88 Suki Chan at the Centre for Chinese Contemporary Art Archive & Library]\n*[https://aaa.org.hk/en/search/search/actors:3486 Suki Chan at the Asia Art Archive]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chan, Suki}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Goldsmiths, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Chelsea College of Arts]]\n[[Category:English mixed media artists]]\n[[Category:Conceptual artists]]\n[[Category:Women conceptual artists]]\n[[Category:English curators]]\n[[Category:21st-century women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{blp sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Artist}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Suki Chan\n| image         = Suki Chan.jpg\n| image_size    = 220\n| caption       = Suki Chan filming Still Point in 2011\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = [[Hong Kong]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| field         = [[Video art]]<br>[[Installation Art]]<br>[[New Media Art]]\n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = ''MEMORY'' (2019),''Lucida'' (2016), ''Still Point'' (2012), ''Sleep Walk Sleep Talk'' (2010), ''Interval II'' (2008)\n| patrons       = \n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n}}\n\n'''Suki Chan''' (born 1977 in [[Hong Kong]]) is an artist and filmmaker whose work uses light, moving image and sound to explore our perception of reality.<ref name=\"tandfonline\">\n{{cite journal\n|title=Suki Chan: The Space Between| doi=10.1080/09528822.2010.502784\n|volume=24\n| issue=5\n|journal=Third Text\n|pages=635\u2013637 |year = 2010|last1 = Kember|first1 = Pamela}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"whitechapelgallery\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.whitechapelgallery.org/shop/product/category_id/183/product_id/1613?session_id=13950876885c2356b81665959d8c35b4155fdfa1a2\n|title=Double Act: Becca Voelcker; Suki Chan\n|publisher=whitechapelgallery.org\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"google\">\n{{cite book\n|title=Contemporary Visual Arts\n|author=Patrick, K.\n|date=2000\n|issue=nos. 28\u201331\n|publisher=G+B Magazines Unlimited\n|issn=1028-5040\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SHZMAAAAYAAJ|isbn=9783908247999\n}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"greenroomutd\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.greenroomutd.org/people/suki-chan\n|title=Suki Chan &#124; www.greenroomutd.org\n|publisher=greenroomutd.org\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref> She is drawn to light as a physical phenomenon, and the role it plays in our constantly shifting daily experience of our environment, be it urban or rural.<ref name=\"artangel\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.artangel.org.uk/about_us/open/open_100/suki_chan|title=Artangel &#124;\n|publisher=artangel.org.uk|accessdate=2014-09-22}} \n</ref> Her pieces vary from photography, film installation to mixed-media sculptures.<ref name=\"a-n\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.a-n.co.uk/artists_talking/artists_stories/single/377223\n|title=Suki Chan &laquo; a-n The Artists Information Company|publisher=a-n.co.uk\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"culturehall\">\n{{cite web|url=http://culturehall.com/suki_chan/biography;jsessionid=5E58FB50DEA085E97B7E1B2DE6C59F30|title=Suki Chan - Artist Biography and CV\n|publisher=culturehall.com|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref>\n\nChan is based in London and is represented by Tintype Gallery.<ref name=\"tintypegallery\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tintypegallery.com/artists/suki-chan/|title=Suki Chan|publisher=tintypegallery.com|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref> She is also a visiting lecturer at the Royal College of Art.\n\n==Education==\n1996: Foundation in Art and Design- Winchester School of Art\n\n1999: BA Fine Art- Goldsmiths\n\n2008: MA Fine Art Chelsea\n\n==Commmissions==\nChan has been commissioned by various organisations to produce work for both galleries and public spaces; including [[Science Gallery Dublin]], <ref name=\"science-gallery-dublin\">{{cite web|url=https://dublin.sciencegallery.com/seeing|title=SEEING|publisher=Science Gallery|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> Film and Video Umbrella,<ref name=\"fvu\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.fvu.co.uk/projects/detail/artists/suki-chan\n|title=Suki Chan &#124; Commissions &#124; Projects &#124; \n|publisher=Film and Video Umbrella\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref> [[Centre for Chinese Contemporary Art]],<ref name=\"CFCCA archive\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://archive.cfcca.org.uk/index.php/Detail/entities/88\n|title= CFCCA Archive: Person: Chan, Suki, artist, (b.1977)\n|publisher=[[Centre for Chinese Contemporary Art]]\n|accessdate=2018-11-11}}\n</ref> The Young Foundation, [[Art on the Underground]] <ref name=\"tfl\">{{cite web|url=http://art.tfl.gov.uk/projects/current/artist/9220|title=Art on the Underground - Current Projects|publisher=art.tfl.gov.uk|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref> and [[Aspex Gallery]].<ref name=\"whitechapelgallery\"/><ref name=\"google3\">{{cite book|title=A Hundred Seas Rising|author1=Chan, S.|author2=Bushnell, J.|date=2012|publisher=Aspex|isbn=9780955025846|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_3q6kQEACAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nChan\u2019s work is included in the collections of the [[Museum of London]],<ref name=\"museumoflondon\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/corporate/press-media/press-releases/sleep-walk-sleep-talk/\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131122094048/http://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/corporate/press-media/press-releases/sleep-walk-sleep-talk/\n|archive-date=2013-11-22\n|url-status=dead\n|title=Sleep walk sleep talk\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref> [[University of Salford]] Arts Collection,<ref name=\"salford art collection\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://artcollection.salford.ac.uk/chinese-contemporary-art/\n|title=New Collection of Chinese Contemporary Art\n|publisher=[[University of Salford]]\n|accessdate=2018-11-11}}</ref> [[University of the Arts London|University of the Arts]] Art Collection, [[David Roberts Art Foundation]] and the [[Ingram Collection of Modern British Art|Ingram Collection]].<ref name=\"ingramcollection\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.ingramcollection.com/artists/suki-chan\n|title=Suki Chan &laquo; The Ingram Collection of Modern British Art\n|publisher=ingramcollection.com\n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}\n</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2008, she was nominated for the Northern Art Prize<ref name=\"northernartprize\">{{cite web|url=http://www.northernartprize.org.uk/2008-prize|title=2008 Prize Northern Art Prize|publisher=northernartprize.org.uk|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref><ref name=\"a-n2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.a-n.co.uk/artists_talking/article/458239|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319044140/http://www.a-n.co.uk/artists_talking/article/458239 |archive-date=2014-03-19 |url-status=dead|title=Northern Art Prize 2008 &#124; Artists talking &#124; a-n|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref> and in 2010, she was shortlisted for the Renaissance Art Prize.<ref name=\"esteri\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icilondon.esteri.it/IIC_Londra/webform/SchedaEvento.aspx?id=554|title=Italian Cultural Institute London|publisher=icilondon.esteri.it|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Chan was one of the 6 young British artists featured in the BBC\u2019s series [[School of Saatchi]].<ref name=\"saatchiart\">{{cite web|url=http://magazine.saatchiart.com/articles/artnews/london-solo-show-for-bbc-school-of-saatchi-finalist-suki-chan|title=London Solo Show for BBC School of Saatchi Finalist Suki Chan : Saatchi Art Magazine : News and Updates for Art Lovers|publisher=magazine.saatchiart.com|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref><ref name=\"thebookoftravels\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebookoftravels.org/acknowledgements/suki-chan|title=Suki Chan &#124; The Book of Travels|publisher=thebookoftravels.org|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref> On the show, [[Tracey Emin]] who said that her work was better than some established artists. \"The film's flipping brilliant,\" she said. \"There's a few artists' names come to mind when I saw it but this knocks spots off them.\"<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/art-news/6624377/Charles-Saatchi-hunts-for-new-star-on-artists-answer-to-X-Factor.html|title=Charles Saatchi hunts for new star on artists' answer to X Factor - Telegraph|publisher=telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref> Chan\u2019s work also received a positive review in The Guardian newspaper from the art critic Robert Clark who wrote \u201cSuki Chan\u2019s art makes us wonder in more ways than one. It enables us to treasure the wonder of the world through daring to suggest the dreadful cost of the loss of such wonderful phenomena.\u201d<ref name=\"thebookoftravels\"/><ref name=\"saatchionline\">{{cite web|url=http://ap.saatchionline.com/art/Photography-Sleep-Walk-Sleep-Talk-film-still/11145/1434865/view|title=Saatchi Art Artist: Suki Chan; Color 2009 Photography \"Sleep Walk Sleep Talk, film still\"|publisher=ap.saatchionline.com|accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref>\n\n==Residencies==\nIn partnership with Bluecoat and [[Arts Council England]], Chan was invited to be one of the artists in residence at the Belong care village, Crewe. Chan interviewed residents which formed the basis of her project, CONSCIOUS.<ref name=\"guardian_residency\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/jun/26/arts-care-homes-healthy|title='It helps residents stay healthy': the benefits of arts in care homes|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Bluecoat_residency\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebluecoat.org.uk/content/-suki-chan|title='Suki Chan, Feb 19|publisher=Bluecoat|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Arts_Council_Conscious\">{{cite web|url=https://www.artscouncil.org.uk/long-read/conscious|title=CONSCIOUS Suki Chan|publisher=Arts Council England|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Chan completed a residency at the Osteopathic Centre for Children, producing 1,000 origami cranes for their permanent installation at the charity's Manchester base.<ref name=\"Manchester_Evening_News_Residency\">{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/hatton-helps-launch-kids-project-1077141|title=Hatton helps launch kids' project|publisher=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian_Residency_2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/jan/26/northerner.martinwainwright|title=\nStop the tramlines, I want them cut off|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sukichan.co.uk/ Official website]\n*[http://archive.cfcca.org.uk/index.php/Detail/entities/88 Suki Chan at the Centre for Chinese Contemporary Art Archive & Library]\n*[https://aaa.org.hk/en/search/search/actors:3486 Suki Chan at the Asia Art Archive]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chan, Suki}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Goldsmiths, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Chelsea College of Arts]]\n[[Category:English mixed media artists]]\n[[Category:Conceptual artists]]\n[[Category:Women conceptual artists]]\n[[Category:English curators]]\n[[Category:21st-century women artists]]\n", "name_user": "Hikaridranz", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suki_Chan"}
{"title_page": "Andr\u00e9e Jeglertz", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name          = Andr\u00e9e Jeglertz\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Andr\u00e9e Alexander Jeglertz\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1972|2|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Malm\u00f6]], Sweden\n| height         = \n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub    = \n| youthyears1    = 1985\u20131990\n| youthclubs1    = [[Malm\u00f6 FF]]\n| years1         = 1991\u20131992\n| clubs1         = [[Malm\u00f6 FF]]\n| caps1          = 25\n| goals1         = 3\n| years2         = 1991\n| clubs2         = \u2192 [[IFK Trelleborg]] (loan)\n| caps2          = \n| goals2         = \n| years3         = 1993\u20131996\n| clubs3         = [[Ume\u00e5 FC]]\n| caps3          = 83\n| goals3         = 1\n| years4         = 1997\u20131999\n| clubs4         = [[IFK H\u00e4ssleholm]]\n| caps4          = 67\n| goals4         = 11\n| years5         = 2000\u20132001\n| clubs5         = [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]]\n| caps5          = \n| goals5         = \n| years6         = 2002\n| clubs6         = [[Ume\u00e5 FC]]\n| caps6          = \n| goals6         = \n| years7         = 2003\u20132004\n| clubs7         = [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]]\n| caps7          = \n| goals7         = \n| totalcaps      = \n| totalgoals     = \n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1  = [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden U21]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  = 2003\u20132004\n| managerclubs1  = [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]] (player coach)\n| manageryears2  = 2004\u20132008\n| managerclubs2  = [[Ume\u00e5 IK]]\n| manageryears3  = 2009\n| managerclubs3  = [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll|Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]]\n| manageryears4  = 2010\u20132016\n| managerclubs4  = [[Finland women's national football team|Finland women]]\n| manageryears5  = 2017\u20132018\n| managerclubs5  = [[Ume\u00e5 FC]]\n}}\n\n'''Andr\u00e9e Alexander Jeglertz''' (born 14 February 1972) is a Swedish [[association football|football]] manager and former professional player. He is an assistant coach for the [[Canada women's national soccer team|Canadian women's national team]].\n\n==Career==\n===Playing career===\nA [[defender (association football)|defender]], Jeglertz played 25 games in the [[Allsvenskan]] for [[Malm\u00f6 FF]] and also played club football for [[IFK Trelleborg]], [[Ume\u00e5 FC]], [[IFK Hasselholm]] and [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]].<ref>{{UEFA coach|20280|Andr\u00e9e Jeglertz|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=7 July 2013}}</ref> He earned three [[Cap (sports)|caps]] for the [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Swedish under-21 national side]].<ref name = \"Nordsjernan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nordstjernan.com/news/sports/976/|title=DIF turns to women's coach to lead A team|accessdate=24 November 2009|author=Chipp Reid|publisher=Nordsjernan}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching career===\nJeglertz moved from [[Ume\u00e5 IK]] to [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll|Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]] for the 2009 season, having previously also coached [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]] for one season.<ref name = \"Nordsjernan\"/> While at Ume\u00e5, Jeglertz won the [[Damallsvenskan|Damallsvenskan Manager of the Year]] award twice, and won the [[UEFA Women's Champions League]] in [[2003\u201304 UEFA Women's Cup|2004]].<ref name = \"Nordsjernan\"/> He was awarded as the [[Finnish Football Manager of the Year]] in 2012.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Djurg\u00e5rdens IF managers}}\n{{Finland Squad 2013 UEFA Women's European Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jeglertz, Andree}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Swedish footballers]]\n[[Category:Allsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:Malm\u00f6 FF players]]\n[[Category:IFK Trelleborg players]]\n[[Category:Ume\u00e5 FC players]]\n[[Category:IFK H\u00e4ssleholm players]]\n[[Category:Swedish football managers]]\n[[Category:Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll managers]]\n[[Category:Finland women's national football team managers]]\n\n\n{{Sweden-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name          = Andr\u00e9e Jeglertz\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Andr\u00e9e Alexander Jeglertz\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1972|2|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Malm\u00f6]], Sweden\n| height         = \n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub    = \n| youthyears1    = 1985\u20131990\n| youthclubs1    = [[Malm\u00f6 FF]]\n| years1         = 1991\u20131992\n| clubs1         = [[Malm\u00f6 FF]]\n| caps1          = 25\n| goals1         = 3\n| years2         = 1991\n| clubs2         = \u2192 [[IFK Trelleborg]] (loan)\n| caps2          = \n| goals2         = \n| years3         = 1993\u20131996\n| clubs3         = [[Ume\u00e5 FC]]\n| caps3          = 83\n| goals3         = 1\n| years4         = 1997\u20131999\n| clubs4         = [[IFK H\u00e4ssleholm]]\n| caps4          = 67\n| goals4         = 11\n| years5         = 2000\u20132001\n| clubs5         = [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]]\n| caps5          = \n| goals5         = \n| years6         = 2002\n| clubs6         = [[Ume\u00e5 FC]]\n| caps6          = \n| goals6         = \n| years7         = 2003\u20132004\n| clubs7         = [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]]\n| caps7          = \n| goals7         = \n| totalcaps      = \n| totalgoals     = \n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1  = [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden U21]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  = 2003\u20132004\n| managerclubs1  = [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]] (player coach)\n| manageryears2  = 2004\u20132008\n| managerclubs2  = [[Ume\u00e5 IK]]\n| manageryears3  = 2009\n| managerclubs3  = [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll|Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]]\n| manageryears4  = 2010\u20132016\n| managerclubs4  = [[Finland women's national football team|Finland women]]\n| manageryears5  = 2017\u20132018\n| managerclubs5  = [[Ume\u00e5 FC]]\n}}\n\n'''Andr\u00e9e Alexander Jeglertz''' (born 14 February 1972) is a Swedish [[association football|football]] manager and former professional player. He is an assistant coach for the [[Canada women's national soccer team|Canadian women's national team]].\n\n==Career==\n===Playing career===\nA [[defender (association football)|defender]], Jeglertz played 25 games in the [[Allsvenskan]] for [[Malm\u00f6 FF]] and also played club football for [[IFK Trelleborg]], [[Ume\u00e5 FC]], [[IFK Hasselholm]] and [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]].<ref>{{UEFA coach|20280|Andr\u00e9e Jeglertz|accessdate=17 July 2013|date=7 July 2013}}</ref> He earned three [[Cap (sports)|caps]] for the [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Swedish under-21 national side]].<ref name = \"Nordsjernan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nordstjernan.com/news/sports/976/|title=DIF turns to women's coach to lead A team|accessdate=24 November 2009|author=Chipp Reid|publisher=Nordsjernan}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching career===\nJeglertz moved from [[Ume\u00e5 IK]] to [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll|Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]] for the 2009 season, having previously also coached [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]] for one season.<ref name = \"Nordsjernan\"/> While at Ume\u00e5, Jeglertz won the [[Damallsvenskan|Damallsvenskan Manager of the Year]] award twice, and won the [[UEFA Women's Champions League]] in [[2003\u201304 UEFA Women's Cup|2004]].<ref name = \"Nordsjernan\"/> He was awarded as the [[Finnish Football Manager of the Year]] in 2012.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Djurg\u00e5rdens IF managers}}\n{{Finland Squad 2013 UEFA Women's European Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jeglertz, Andree}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish footballers]]\n[[Category:Allsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:Malm\u00f6 FF players]]\n[[Category:IFK Trelleborg players]]\n[[Category:Ume\u00e5 FC players]]\n[[Category:IFK H\u00e4ssleholm players]]\n[[Category:Swedish football managers]]\n[[Category:Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll managers]]\n[[Category:Finland women's national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n\n\n{{Sweden-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix playing position category.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andr%C3%A9e_Jeglertz"}
